const SAA_QUESTIONS = [{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company stores sensitive customer PII in an S3 bucket. The security team requires that all data be encrypted using a key they fully control and can rotate on demand. Which solution meets this requirement?","options":["A. Enable SSE-S3 on the bucket","B. Enable SSE-KMS using a customer-managed KMS key","C. Enable SSE-KMS using the AWS-managed S3 key","D. Use client-side encryption with an AWS-generated key"],"answer":1,"explain":"SSE-KMS with a customer-managed key (CMK) gives the customer full control over key policy, rotation, and auditing via CloudTrail. SSE-S3 uses AWS-managed keys. The AWS-managed S3 key cannot be controlled or rotated by the customer. Client-side encryption with AWS-generated keys does not give full control."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A Solutions Architect needs to ensure EC2 instances in a private subnet can access AWS services without traversing the public internet. Which solution achieves this with the least operational overhead?","options":["A. Deploy a NAT Gateway in a public subnet","B. Create VPC endpoints for the required AWS services","C. Set up a Site-to-Site VPN to AWS","D. Use an internet gateway with restrictive security groups"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC endpoints (Gateway or Interface) allow private connectivity to AWS services without internet access. NAT Gateway routes traffic to the public internet. VPN and internet gateway both involve internet exposure."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A web application on EC2 is receiving SQL injection attacks. The security team wants to block these at the network edge with minimal application changes. What should the architect recommend?","options":["A. Configure Security Groups to block malicious IPs","B. Deploy AWS WAF with SQL injection match rules in front of the Application Load Balancer","C. Enable AWS Shield Advanced on the EC2 instances","D. Use VPC NACLs to filter HTTP traffic"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS WAF inspects HTTP/HTTPS content and can block SQL injection patterns using managed rule groups or custom rules. Security Groups and NACLs operate at layer 3/4 and cannot inspect HTTP payloads. Shield Advanced protects against DDoS, not application-layer injection attacks."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An application needs to call AWS APIs from EC2 instances. The security team prohibits storing long-term credentials on instances. What is the correct approach?","options":["A. Store IAM user access keys in environment variables","B. Use AWS Secrets Manager to store and retrieve IAM keys","C. Attach an IAM role to the EC2 instances","D. Hardcode credentials in the application configuration file"],"answer":2,"explain":"IAM roles for EC2 provide temporary credentials via the instance metadata service (IMDS). These are automatically rotated and require no static credentials. Storing long-term keys anywhere on the instance (env vars, files, Secrets Manager) is against best practices."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company wants to prevent anyone, including the root account, from disabling AWS CloudTrail logs in their organization. Which approach enforces this?","options":["A. Enable MFA Delete on the CloudTrail S3 bucket","B. Create a Service Control Policy (SCP) that denies cloudtrail:StopLogging and attach it to the root OU","C. Enable CloudTrail log file validation","D. Configure CloudTrail with a dedicated AWS account"],"answer":1,"explain":"SCPs in AWS Organizations can deny specific actions across all accounts, including member accounts with admin users. Even the root user of a member account cannot override an SCP. MFA Delete protects the S3 bucket but not the trail itself. Log validation detects tampering but doesn't prevent disabling."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An application uses Amazon RDS. The security team requires that database passwords be automatically rotated every 30 days and never stored in code. What is the recommended solution?","options":["A. Store the password in an S3 bucket with server-side encryption","B. Use AWS Secrets Manager with automatic rotation enabled","C. Use AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store Standard tier","D. Encrypt the password using KMS and store in DynamoDB"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Secrets Manager natively integrates with RDS for automatic password rotation. It stores and retrieves secrets securely via API, eliminating hardcoded credentials. Parameter Store does not support automatic rotation for RDS. S3 and DynamoDB are not designed for secret management with automatic rotation."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to federate corporate Active Directory users into AWS without creating IAM users for each person. Which solution achieves this?","options":["A. Create an IAM group for each AD group and sync users manually","B. Use AWS Directory Service AD Connector to proxy authentication and assume IAM roles via SAML federation","C. Provide all users with a shared IAM user credential","D. Use Amazon Cognito User Pools to mirror AD accounts"],"answer":1,"explain":"AD Connector proxies authentication requests to on-premises AD. Combined with SAML 2.0 federation, users authenticate against AD and receive temporary AWS credentials via AssumeRoleWithSAML. No IAM users are created. Shared credentials violate least-privilege principles."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A Solutions Architect is reviewing S3 bucket policies and finds a bucket with 's3:GetObject' allowed for principal '*'. What is the security risk and correct remediation?","options":["A. The bucket is publicly readable; add a condition for aws:SecureTransport only","B. The bucket is publicly readable; remove the wildcard principal or restrict to specific AWS accounts/roles","C. The risk is minimal if the objects are encrypted with SSE-S3","D. Add a bucket ACL to override the bucket policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Principal '*' makes the bucket publicly accessible to anyone on the internet. The correct fix is to remove the wildcard or scope it to specific principals. Encryption does not prevent public read access — anyone can still retrieve and decrypt SSE-S3 objects. ACLs cannot override a permissive bucket policy."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A multi-account AWS environment needs centralized security findings from GuardDuty, Security Hub, and Inspector. Which service aggregates findings across accounts with the least complexity?","options":["A. AWS Config aggregator","B. AWS Security Hub with a delegated administrator account","C. Amazon CloudWatch cross-account dashboards","D. AWS Trusted Advisor"],"answer":1,"explain":"Security Hub aggregates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, and more across all accounts in an AWS Organization when a delegated administrator is configured. Config aggregators focus on configuration compliance. CloudWatch dashboards don't aggregate security findings. Trusted Advisor has limited cross-account capability."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company runs a public API on API Gateway. They want to allow only requests from their corporate IP range and block all others. What is the simplest way to implement this?","options":["A. Deploy a WAF WebACL with an IP set allow rule and associate it with API Gateway","B. Configure a Security Group on the API Gateway","C. Use a Lambda authorizer to check request IPs","D. Enable API Gateway resource policies with IP conditions"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS WAF with an IP set allow rule attached to API Gateway is the most straightforward approach. API Gateway does not support security groups (it is a managed service, not VPC-native). Resource policies can also restrict IPs but WAF provides more flexibility and is purpose-built for this. Lambda authorizers add latency and cost for simple IP filtering."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An S3 bucket hosts a static website. The architect must ensure all traffic uses HTTPS and HTTP requests are redirected. Which combination achieves this?","options":["A. Enable S3 static website hosting with HTTPS — S3 static hosting natively supports HTTPS","B. Put CloudFront in front of S3, configure the CloudFront distribution to redirect HTTP to HTTPS, use an ACM certificate","C. Attach an SSL certificate directly to the S3 bucket","D. Use an Application Load Balancer with ACM certificate in front of S3"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 static website hosting does not support HTTPS natively. CloudFront with an ACM certificate provides HTTPS termination and can enforce HTTP-to-HTTPS redirects via viewer protocol policy. ALB cannot serve S3 static website content directly without additional configuration."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company must ensure EC2 instances in a VPC can only communicate with other instances in specific security groups. They want to avoid managing IP address-based rules. What should they use?","options":["A. VPC Network ACLs with CIDR-based rules","B. Reference security groups as sources in inbound security group rules","C. Use AWS Network Firewall with IP-based rules","D. VPC flow logs with automated blocking via Lambda"],"answer":1,"explain":"Security groups support referencing other security groups as source/destination. This eliminates the need to track IP addresses and automatically applies to all instances in the referenced group. NACLs require IP-based rules. Network Firewall and Lambda-based blocking add operational complexity."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An organization wants to detect if IAM credentials are being used from an unusual geographic location. Which AWS service provides this capability out of the box?","options":["A. AWS Config with custom rules","B. Amazon GuardDuty","C. AWS CloudTrail with Athena queries","D. AWS Trusted Advisor"],"answer":1,"explain":"GuardDuty uses machine learning and threat intelligence to detect anomalous behavior including credential access from unusual geolocations (finding type: UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/ConsoleLoginSuccess.B). Config tracks configuration changes. CloudTrail requires manual analysis. Trusted Advisor does not provide behavioral threat detection."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to share encrypted AMIs across multiple AWS accounts. The AMI is encrypted with a customer-managed KMS key. What additional step is required?","options":["A. Copy the AMI to each account without encryption","B. Share the KMS key policy to allow the target accounts to use the key, then share the AMI","C. Re-encrypt the AMI with the AWS-managed EC2 key before sharing","D. Enable cross-account AMI sharing in AWS Organizations — it handles key permissions automatically"],"answer":1,"explain":"When sharing an encrypted AMI, the target account must have kms:DescribeKey, kms:ReEncrypt*, kms:CreateGrant, and kms:Decrypt permissions on the KMS key. Both the AMI and the key must be shared. AWS does not automatically handle this — explicit key policy updates are required."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A Lambda function needs to read a secret from Secrets Manager. The function is also logging to CloudWatch. Using least-privilege IAM, which policy should be attached to the Lambda execution role?","options":["A. AdministratorAccess managed policy","B. A custom policy allowing secretsmanager:GetSecretValue for the specific secret ARN and logs:CreateLogGroup, logs:CreateLogStream, logs:PutLogEvents for the log group","C. AmazonSecretsManagerReadWrite plus CloudWatchFullAccess","D. AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole only — it includes Secrets Manager access"],"answer":1,"explain":"Least privilege requires granting only the specific actions on specific resources needed. A custom policy scoped to the exact secret ARN and log group is correct. Managed policies like ReadWrite or FullAccess grant far more permissions than needed. AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole only grants logging, not Secrets Manager access."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to enforce that all EBS volumes created in an AWS account are encrypted by default. What is the most efficient approach?","options":["A. Use an SCP to deny ec2:CreateVolume unless encryption is specified","B. Enable EBS encryption by default in the EC2 console or via AWS Config remediation","C. Use a CloudFormation StackSet to enforce encryption in all regions","D. Deploy an EventBridge rule to delete unencrypted volumes on creation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Enabling EBS default encryption is an account-level setting that automatically encrypts all new EBS volumes and snapshots. This is the simplest and most reliable approach. SCPs add complexity. CloudFormation StackSets only cover resources created via CloudFormation. EventBridge-based deletion is reactive and causes data loss risk."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An application needs to allow users to upload files directly to S3 without routing through an application server. The uploads should be secure and expire after 15 minutes. What mechanism enables this?","options":["A. Make the S3 bucket public and use client-side encryption","B. Generate a pre-signed URL with a 15-minute expiration from the application server","C. Create a temporary IAM user and provide credentials to the client","D. Use an S3 Transfer Acceleration URL with a time-based token"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-signed URLs grant temporary, time-limited access to perform a specific S3 operation (PUT in this case) without exposing AWS credentials to the client. They are generated server-side using the application's IAM credentials. Public buckets expose all objects. Temporary IAM users are operationally complex and not recommended."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company wants to detect and alert when an S3 bucket containing sensitive data is made publicly accessible. Which solution provides near-real-time detection?","options":["A. Enable S3 server access logging and analyze with Athena daily","B. Enable Amazon Macie and configure findings to trigger an EventBridge rule and SNS notification","C. Configure AWS Config rule s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited with SNS notification","D. Use S3 Block Public Access at the account level — it alerts automatically"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Config's s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited rule detects non-compliant buckets within minutes and can trigger SNS notifications or auto-remediation. Macie focuses on sensitive data discovery and PII detection rather than ACL/policy changes. S3 Block Public Access prevents changes but doesn't send alerts. Athena analysis is not near-real-time."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A Solutions Architect must design a solution where EC2 instances in a private subnet can retrieve secrets from Secrets Manager without internet access. What should they deploy?","options":["A. A NAT Gateway in the public subnet","B. An interface VPC endpoint for Secrets Manager","C. A public IP on the EC2 instances","D. An S3 gateway endpoint and cache secrets in S3"],"answer":1,"explain":"An interface VPC endpoint for AWS Secrets Manager (com.amazonaws.region.secretsmanager) allows private subnet resources to call Secrets Manager APIs without internet access. NAT Gateway routes to the public internet. Public IPs on private subnet instances require an internet gateway which may violate security requirements."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An auditor requires proof that no S3 object was modified or deleted after being written. Which feature provides immutability and legal hold capabilities?","options":["A. S3 Versioning with MFA Delete","B. S3 Object Lock in COMPLIANCE mode","C. S3 Replication to a separate account","D. S3 Intelligent-Tiering with access logging"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Object Lock in COMPLIANCE mode prevents objects from being deleted or overwritten for a defined retention period — even by the root account. GOVERNANCE mode allows users with special permissions to override. MFA Delete prevents deletion but doesn't enforce retention periods. Replication doesn't prevent modification of the source."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company's security policy requires all API calls to AWS be logged and the logs must be tamper-evident. CloudTrail is already enabled. What additional step ensures log integrity?","options":["A. Enable CloudTrail log file validation — it creates a SHA-256 hash digest file for each log file","B. Replicate CloudTrail logs to a second region","C. Enable S3 versioning on the CloudTrail bucket","D. Enable CloudTrail Insights to detect unusual API patterns"],"answer":0,"explain":"CloudTrail log file validation creates a digitally signed digest file every hour that can be used to verify whether log files were modified, deleted, or unchanged after delivery. This provides cryptographic proof of log integrity. Versioning and replication protect availability but not integrity proof. Insights detects anomalies, not tampering."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A microservices application running in ECS needs to authenticate to an RDS database. The security team wants credentials rotated automatically without restarting containers. What is the best approach?","options":["A. Store credentials in ECS task definition environment variables","B. Use AWS Secrets Manager with ECS integration — the ECS agent injects the secret and Secrets Manager handles rotation","C. Bake the database password into the Docker image","D. Use SSM Parameter Store SecureString and restart tasks after each rotation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Secrets Manager integrates natively with ECS task definitions to inject secrets at container startup and supports automatic rotation. Tasks don't need to be restarted when Secrets Manager rotates the RDS password because ECS can be configured to retrieve the latest version. Hardcoding or storing in environment variables are security anti-patterns."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company is using AWS Organizations and wants to prevent member accounts from leaving the organization. Which control achieves this?","options":["A. Remove the member account's IAM billing access","B. Create an SCP that denies organizations:LeaveOrganization","C. Enable AWS Config in all member accounts","D. Apply a permission boundary to all IAM users in member accounts"],"answer":1,"explain":"An SCP denying organizations:LeaveOrganization attached to all OUs or the root prevents member accounts from leaving. SCPs override any IAM policy in member accounts. Config tracks configuration changes but doesn't prevent organization changes. Permission boundaries apply to IAM entities, not account-level organization actions."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An EC2 instance is compromised and is making outbound connections to known malicious IP addresses. Which AWS service would have detected this automatically?","options":["A. AWS Inspector","B. AWS Config","C. Amazon GuardDuty","D. AWS Trusted Advisor"],"answer":2,"explain":"GuardDuty analyzes VPC Flow Logs, CloudTrail, and DNS logs to detect malicious activity including communication with known bad IPs (finding: Backdoor:EC2/C&CActivity.B). Inspector scans for vulnerabilities and CVEs. Config tracks configuration state. Trusted Advisor covers best practice checks, not threat detection."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to provide contractors temporary AWS console access for 8 hours without creating permanent IAM users. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. Create temporary IAM users and delete them after 8 hours","B. Use AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) with time-limited assignments or assume a role via STS with MaxSessionDuration set to 8 hours","C. Share the root account credentials with time-based restrictions","D. Use Amazon Cognito for console access"],"answer":1,"explain":"STS AssumeRole with a maximum session duration of up to 12 hours provides temporary credentials without permanent IAM users. IAM Identity Center with assignment expiry is also a valid approach. Temporary IAM users require manual lifecycle management. Sharing root credentials is a critical security violation. Cognito is for application authentication, not AWS console access."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A regulated company must ensure that sensitive data in S3 is never transmitted without encryption in transit. How can they enforce this?","options":["A. Enable S3 default encryption","B. Add a bucket policy that denies any request where aws:SecureTransport is false","C. Enable HTTPS on the application accessing S3","D. Configure AWS Config to detect unencrypted S3 requests"],"answer":1,"explain":"A bucket policy with Condition: {Bool: {aws:SecureTransport: false}} and Effect: Deny blocks any unencrypted HTTP requests to the bucket at the API level. Default encryption protects data at rest, not in transit. Application-level HTTPS doesn't protect all clients. Config detects but doesn't enforce."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company uses multiple AWS accounts and wants to centralize DNS resolution between a shared services VPC and workload VPCs. What enables private DNS resolution across VPCs?","options":["A. Create public Route 53 hosted zones and share across accounts","B. Use Route 53 Resolver with inbound/outbound endpoints and Route 53 Resolver rules shared via RAM","C. Peer all VPCs and update each VPC's DHCP options set","D. Deploy a BIND DNS server in the shared VPC and use as forwarder"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 Resolver with Resolver rules shared through AWS RAM allows centralized DNS forwarding between VPCs across accounts without routing all DNS through a custom server. Simple VPC peering doesn't resolve private hosted zones across accounts. BIND servers add operational overhead. Public hosted zones expose internal DNS."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An application stores encryption keys in code. The security team requires these be removed and managed centrally with key rotation. The application currently uses AES-256. Which AWS service replaces this?","options":["A. AWS Certificate Manager (ACM)","B. AWS Key Management Service (KMS) with GenerateDataKey API","C. AWS CloudHSM for direct AES operations","D. IAM role policies with key ARN references"],"answer":1,"explain":"KMS GenerateDataKey returns a plaintext data key and encrypted copy — the application uses the plaintext key for AES-256 encryption then discards it, storing only the encrypted key. KMS manages the master key with automatic rotation. ACM manages TLS certificates. CloudHSM is for workloads requiring dedicated HSMs and FIPS 140-2 Level 3. IAM doesn't manage encryption keys."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to ensure that developers cannot launch EC2 instances larger than t3.medium in the development account. What enforces this?","options":["A. Create an IAM policy with a condition on ec2:InstanceType and attach it to developers","B. Use an SCP to deny ec2:RunInstances unless ec2:InstanceType matches allowed types, attach to the dev OU","C. Configure AWS Config with an ec2-instance-type rule","D. Use Service Quotas to limit instance counts"],"answer":1,"explain":"An SCP at the OU level with a Deny for ec2:RunInstances unless the instance type is in the allowed list enforces this across all users in the dev account. IAM policies can be overridden by admins. Config detects non-compliant instances after launch but doesn't prevent them. Service Quotas limit counts, not types."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company's application writes sensitive logs to CloudWatch Logs. The security team requires these logs be encrypted with a customer-managed key. How is this configured?","options":["A. CloudWatch Logs automatically encrypts all logs with KMS — no configuration needed","B. Associate a KMS CMK with the CloudWatch Logs log group using the associate-kms-key API","C. Enable S3 SSE-KMS on the S3 bucket used by CloudWatch Logs export","D. Enable CloudTrail encryption and route logs through CloudTrail"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch Logs supports encryption at rest using KMS CMKs. You associate a key with a log group using the associate-kms-key API or at creation time. The default encryption uses AES-256 but is not customer-managed. Exporting to S3 is a separate action. CloudTrail encryption is for CloudTrail logs only."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company has a compliance requirement that all network traffic between VPCs must be inspected for threats. They use AWS Transit Gateway. Where should they insert an inspection layer?","options":["A. Deploy security groups on all EC2 instances in both VPCs","B. Insert an AWS Network Firewall in a centralized inspection VPC and route all inter-VPC traffic through it via Transit Gateway route tables","C. Enable VPC Flow Logs and analyze with Athena","D. Use GuardDuty to inspect all transit gateway traffic"],"answer":1,"explain":"A centralized inspection architecture with AWS Network Firewall deployed in a dedicated inspection VPC, with Transit Gateway routing tables directing spoke VPC traffic through it, enables stateful deep packet inspection between VPCs. Security groups don't inspect traffic content. Flow Logs are for analysis, not inspection. GuardDuty uses Flow Logs metadata, not payload inspection."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A Lambda function is being invoked by an S3 event notification. An attacker has modified the S3 event to inject unexpected data into the Lambda function. What security control reduces this risk?","options":["A. Use an S3 bucket policy to prevent external PUT operations","B. Add input validation within the Lambda function code to sanitize and validate all incoming event data","C. Enable Lambda code signing","D. Encrypt the Lambda function with KMS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Input validation within Lambda is the primary defense against injection via malformed events. Even trusted event sources can send unexpected data — code should never trust event data without validation. Bucket policies prevent unauthorized uploads but don't validate event content. Code signing ensures code integrity, not input safety. KMS encryption protects code at rest."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to meet PCI DSS requirements that mandate network segmentation of cardholder data. Which VPC design best supports this?","options":["A. Place all resources in the same VPC with security group rules separating tiers","B. Create separate VPCs for cardholder data, application, and management tiers with VPC peering and strict route tables","C. Use a single public subnet for all resources to simplify auditing","D. Deploy all resources in a single private subnet with a NAT gateway"],"answer":1,"explain":"PCI DSS requires logical or physical separation of the cardholder data environment (CDE). Separate VPCs with controlled peering provide stronger segmentation than security groups alone, which can be misconfigured. Single subnet architectures mix traffic and fail PCI segmentation requirements."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company discovered that a former employee's IAM access key is still active and was last used 6 months ago. What is the immediate remediation?","options":["A. Rotate the access key to generate a new one","B. Deactivate or delete the access key immediately and audit all API calls made with it in CloudTrail","C. Change the IAM user's password","D. Move the user to a restricted IAM group"],"answer":1,"explain":"Immediately deactivating or deleting a stale credential prevents unauthorized use. CloudTrail audit of the key's usage reveals if it was accessed maliciously. Rotation generates a new key but the old key remains valid until deleted. Password changes don't affect access keys. Moving to a restricted group doesn't revoke existing key permissions immediately."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An application needs to access AWS services from on-premises servers without storing long-term IAM credentials. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. Create an IAM user with an access key and store on the server","B. Use AWS IAM Roles Anywhere with a certificate authority to issue X.509 certificates for temporary credentials","C. Use an EC2 instance profile from on-premises","D. Hard-code root account credentials in the application configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"IAM Roles Anywhere extends IAM roles to workloads outside AWS using X.509 certificates from a trusted CA. It provides temporary, automatically-rotated credentials without long-term access keys. Instance profiles are only available on EC2. Long-term keys and root credentials are security anti-patterns."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company wants to prevent accidental deletion of critical DynamoDB tables in production. What is the most effective safeguard?","options":["A. Enable DynamoDB Point-in-Time Recovery (PITR)","B. Enable DynamoDB deletion protection on the table","C. Remove dynamodb:DeleteTable permission from all developers","D. Enable AWS Backup for DynamoDB"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB deletion protection is a table-level setting that prevents DeleteTable API calls regardless of IAM permissions. It must be explicitly disabled before a table can be deleted. PITR enables recovery after deletion but doesn't prevent it. IAM permission removal helps but can be bypassed by admins. AWS Backup provides recovery, not prevention."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A financial company must ensure that data at rest in RDS PostgreSQL is encrypted and that the encryption key is dedicated to their environment. Which storage option meets this requirement?","options":["A. Enable RDS encryption with the AWS-managed RDS KMS key (aws/rds)","B. Enable RDS encryption at rest using a customer-managed KMS CMK","C. Use RDS with SSE-S3 encryption","D. Store data in encrypted EBS volumes with default AWS keys"],"answer":1,"explain":"A customer-managed KMS CMK gives dedicated control over key policy, rotation, and auditing. The AWS-managed key (aws/rds) is shared and cannot be controlled by the customer. RDS does not use SSE-S3. RDS manages its own EBS volumes — you can't apply separate EBS encryption settings."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company runs multiple AWS accounts. Security team needs a single pane of glass showing all IAM users across accounts without requiring console access to each account. Which solution provides this?","options":["A. Use AWS Organizations console to list all IAM users","B. Use IAM Access Analyzer with a delegated admin account","C. Deploy AWS Config aggregator with the iam-user-no-policies-check rule across all accounts","D. Use AWS Security Hub with cross-account aggregation and IAM findings"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Config aggregator collects configuration data from multiple accounts. The iam-user-no-policies-check rule (and similar IAM rules) provides visibility into IAM user configurations. IAM Access Analyzer focuses on external access risks. Organizations doesn't enumerate IAM users. Security Hub focuses on security findings, not IAM user inventory."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company wants to enforce that all Lambda functions use VPC networking and that no Lambda function has internet access. Which control achieves this across all accounts?","options":["A. Create an IAM policy denying lambda:CreateFunction without VPC config","B. Use AWS Config rule lambda-inside-vpc and lambda-function-public-access-prohibited with auto-remediation","C. Set a VPC as default for Lambda in each account's settings","D. Deploy an SCP denying lambda:CreateFunction — developers must request exceptions"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config rules can detect Lambda functions not in a VPC or with public access, and auto-remediation can invoke an SSM Automation or Lambda function to remediate. This is detective + corrective. Lambda doesn't have an account-level VPC default setting. An SCP completely blocking Lambda creation is too restrictive for normal operations."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company hosts a REST API on Amazon API Gateway. They need to authenticate API consumers using JSON Web Tokens (JWT) issued by their own identity provider. What is the most appropriate authentication method?","options":["A. API Gateway Lambda authorizer that calls the identity provider","B. API Gateway JWT authorizer configured with the identity provider's JWKS URI","C. IAM authorization with SigV4 signing","D. API keys with usage plans"],"answer":1,"explain":"API Gateway HTTP APIs support native JWT authorizers that validate tokens using the identity provider's JWKS endpoint without requiring Lambda. This provides low-latency, low-cost token validation. Lambda authorizers add latency and cost. IAM auth requires AWS credentials, not JWT tokens. API keys are for throttling/metering, not authentication."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company must scan all container images for vulnerabilities before they are deployed to production ECS. What is the most automated and integrated approach?","options":["A. Use a third-party vulnerability scanner run manually before each deployment","B. Enable ECR image scanning (enhanced scanning with Amazon Inspector) and block deployments if critical vulnerabilities are found using an EventBridge rule","C. Scan images with AWS Trusted Advisor after deployment","D. Use CloudWatch Container Insights to detect vulnerabilities post-deployment"],"answer":1,"explain":"ECR enhanced scanning with Amazon Inspector automatically scans images on push and continuously for new CVEs. EventBridge rules triggered by Inspector findings can block ECS service updates or pipeline progression. Manual scanning introduces human error. Trusted Advisor doesn't scan container images. Container Insights is for performance monitoring."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An organization must meet a compliance requirement that no S3 data is replicated or stored outside the us-east-1 region. What enforces this at scale?","options":["A. Enable S3 versioning and configure lifecycle policies in each bucket","B. Apply an SCP that denies s3:PutBucketReplication and s3:CreateBucket unless the region is us-east-1","C. Configure S3 Block Public Access at account level","D. Use AWS Config to detect S3 buckets in other regions and delete them"],"answer":1,"explain":"An SCP can restrict S3 bucket creation to a specific region using the aws:RequestedRegion condition key, and can deny replication configuration. This is preventive. Config is detective. Block Public Access addresses public access, not data residency. Lifecycle policies manage object retention, not regional restrictions."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company's security team wants to receive alerts when root account login occurs. Which combination of services provides this?","options":["A. Enable CloudTrail, create a CloudWatch Logs metric filter for root login events, and create a CloudWatch Alarm with SNS notification","B. Enable AWS Config and use the root-account-mfa-enabled rule","C. Enable AWS GuardDuty and set a custom threat list for root account","D. Use IAM credential reports sent to SNS on a schedule"],"answer":0,"explain":"CloudTrail captures all API and console events including root logins. A CloudWatch Logs metric filter on the event source 'aws.signin' and userIdentity type 'Root' triggers an alarm and SNS notification. Config checks MFA status but doesn't alert on login events. GuardDuty can detect anomalous root usage but isn't configured for simple login alerts. Credential reports show last used, not real-time."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A web application needs to authenticate users through social identity providers (Google, Facebook). The application is hosted on EC2. Which AWS service handles this with minimal custom code?","options":["A. AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO)","B. Amazon Cognito User Pools with social identity provider federation","C. AWS STS AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity called directly from the front end","D. Create IAM users for each social identity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cognito User Pools natively federate with social identity providers and handles OIDC/OAuth flows, token management, and user directory. It abstracts the complexity of integrating with each IdP. IAM Identity Center is for workforce identity (employees). Direct STS calls require custom federation code. Creating IAM users for social identities is not scalable."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An attacker is performing a volumetric DDoS attack against a company's Route 53 hosted website. Which AWS services provide automatic DDoS protection at the DNS and infrastructure layer?","options":["A. AWS Shield Standard (automatically enabled) protects Route 53 and CloudFront at the network layer","B. Deploy a WAF rule to block all traffic above a threshold","C. Increase EC2 instance sizes to absorb the attack","D. Enable VPC Flow Logs to detect and manually block attacking IPs"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Shield Standard is automatically enabled for all AWS customers at no cost and provides protection against common DDoS attacks at the network and transport layers for Route 53, CloudFront, and Elastic Load Balancers. WAF operates at the application layer (L7) and isn't designed for volumetric DDoS. Scaling EC2 and manual IP blocking are reactive and insufficient for volumetric attacks."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs a hardware security module (HSM) to perform cryptographic operations for a PKI implementation requiring FIPS 140-2 Level 3 validation. Which AWS service meets this?","options":["A. AWS KMS with a custom key store","B. AWS CloudHSM","C. AWS Secrets Manager with RSA encryption","D. ACM Private CA with hardware backing"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS CloudHSM provides dedicated FIPS 140-2 Level 3 validated HSM hardware. KMS custom key stores integrate with CloudHSM but CloudHSM itself provides the hardware. KMS alone is FIPS 140-2 Level 2. ACM Private CA uses KMS-backed keys, not dedicated hardware. Secrets Manager doesn't perform HSM-grade cryptographic operations."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company stores API keys for third-party services in SSM Parameter Store as SecureString parameters. Multiple Lambda functions access these. The security team wants automatic rotation. What is the recommended upgrade?","options":["A. Migrate to SSM Parameter Store Advanced tier — it supports rotation","B. Migrate to AWS Secrets Manager which supports automatic rotation with custom rotation Lambda functions","C. Store in DynamoDB with a rotation Lambda triggered by EventBridge","D. Use KMS automatic key rotation — it rotates the encryption key and thus the secret value"],"answer":1,"explain":"Secrets Manager supports automatic rotation using Lambda rotation functions. SSM Parameter Store (including Advanced tier) does not support automatic rotation natively. DynamoDB-based rotation is a custom solution adding complexity. KMS automatic rotation rotates the encryption key, not the secret value stored within it."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to prove to auditors that their AWS infrastructure configuration has not drifted from approved baselines over the past 12 months. Which AWS service provides this configuration history?","options":["A. AWS CloudTrail — it records all API calls made over time","B. AWS Config — it records configuration snapshots and change history for all supported resources","C. Amazon CloudWatch — it stores metrics and log data for 15 months","D. AWS Systems Manager Inventory — it collects instance configuration data"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config maintains a continuous record of resource configuration changes and provides a timeline view of how configurations changed. It can also evaluate compliance against rules over time. CloudTrail records API calls but not the resulting resource configuration state. CloudWatch stores metrics and logs, not resource configuration history. Systems Manager Inventory covers EC2 instance metadata, not all AWS resources."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An EC2-based application is transmitting sensitive data to another EC2 instance in the same VPC. The security team requires encryption in transit between the instances. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. VPC traffic is encrypted by default — no additional steps are needed","B. Implement TLS/mTLS between the application components or use AWS Private CA to issue certificates","C. Enable VPC Flow Logs encryption","D. Use an encrypted EBS volume on both instances"],"answer":1,"explain":"Traffic within a VPC is not encrypted by default at the network layer. Application-level TLS/mTLS provides encryption in transit between instances. For higher assurance, mutual TLS (mTLS) with AWS Private CA-issued certificates verifies both sides. VPC Flow Log encryption is for log storage. EBS encryption protects data at rest, not in transit."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company is migrating to AWS and must ensure that no root account API keys exist. How can they verify this efficiently across all accounts in their organization?","options":["A. Log into each account and check the IAM security credentials page","B. Use AWS Organizations and run aws iam generate-credential-report to check root account access keys across accounts","C. Enable AWS Trusted Advisor's Security category — it flags root account access keys","D. Use CloudTrail to search for root API key creation events"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor's Security category includes a check specifically for root account access keys. This provides a quick, automated assessment. IAM credential reports per account work but require accessing each account. Organizations doesn't have a built-in cross-account credential reporting tool. CloudTrail can find creation events but doesn't show current state."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company wants to restrict access to an internal web application hosted on EC2 to only users connected to their corporate VPN. The VPN terminates on-premises and connects to AWS via Direct Connect. How should access be restricted?","options":["A. Configure security groups to allow traffic only from the on-premises VPN CIDR range","B. Use an internet-facing ALB with a WAF IP allow rule","C. Implement Cognito authentication on the application","D. Deploy AWS Client VPN and require authentication for all users"],"answer":0,"explain":"Since traffic from on-premises arrives via Direct Connect with a known CIDR range, security groups can restrict access to only that IP range at no extra cost with no additional services. WAF IP rules also work but add cost and complexity. Cognito adds authentication but doesn't restrict network access. AWS Client VPN is for users connecting without an existing corporate VPN/Direct Connect."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company using AWS Organizations wants to ensure that all new accounts created automatically have GuardDuty enabled. What is the most automated approach?","options":["A. Create a CloudFormation StackSet deployed to all new accounts","B. Configure GuardDuty in the management account with a delegated administrator and enable auto-enable for organization member accounts","C. Use AWS Config to detect accounts without GuardDuty and trigger a Lambda to enable it","D. Require a manual ticket process for account teams to enable GuardDuty"],"answer":1,"explain":"GuardDuty supports AWS Organizations integration. When a delegated administrator account is set up, GuardDuty can be configured to auto-enable on all existing and new member accounts. This is fully automated. StackSets can work but add complexity. Config-based remediation is reactive. Manual processes don't scale."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to protect sensitive data patterns (SSNs, credit card numbers) stored in S3. Which AWS service automatically discovers and alerts on this data?","options":["A. Amazon GuardDuty","B. Amazon Macie","C. AWS Security Hub","D. Amazon Inspector"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Macie uses machine learning to automatically discover sensitive data including PII, financial data, and credentials in S3. GuardDuty detects threats and malicious activity, not data classification. Security Hub aggregates findings. Inspector scans compute resources for vulnerabilities."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"An EC2 instance needs to call a third-party HTTPS endpoint. The security team wants all outbound traffic to be inspected and logged. Which architecture supports this?","options":["A. Route outbound EC2 traffic through an internet gateway with VPC Flow Logs","B. Force traffic through AWS Network Firewall in the VPC and configure stateful rules for the specific endpoint","C. Use a NAT instance with iptables logging","D. Configure CloudWatch agent to log all network connections"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Network Firewall provides stateful, deep packet inspection for both inbound and outbound traffic. Routing EC2 egress through Network Firewall in the VPC allows HTTPS SNI inspection, logging to CloudWatch/S3, and allow/deny rules. Internet gateway with Flow Logs provides IP-level logs only. NAT instances are legacy solutions. CloudWatch agent logs application activity, not network-level traffic."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company must ensure that IAM permissions in their account follow least privilege. They want to identify overly permissive policies that haven't been used in 90 days. Which tool helps?","options":["A. AWS Trusted Advisor","B. IAM Access Advisor — shows last-accessed service data for each IAM entity","C. Amazon GuardDuty with policy anomaly detection","D. AWS Security Hub with CIS benchmark controls"],"answer":1,"explain":"IAM Access Advisor shows the last time each AWS service was accessed by an IAM user, role, or policy. This data helps right-size permissions by removing access to services not used within a time period. Trusted Advisor shows some IAM checks but not per-service access granularity. GuardDuty detects active threats. Security Hub checks best practices but doesn't show access patterns."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company has a strict requirement that no AWS service should be able to access S3 bucket objects unless explicitly granted. Currently, the bucket has no bucket policy. What is the default behavior?","options":["A. All AWS services with IAM roles can access the bucket by default","B. By default, only the bucket owner (the AWS account) has access — no other principal has access unless granted","C. All EC2 instances in the same VPC can access S3 buckets by default","D. AWS-managed services (RDS, Lambda) get read access to all S3 buckets by default"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 follows a deny-by-default model. Without explicit grants via bucket policy, ACL, or IAM policy, no principal other than the bucket owner account has access. IAM roles need both the IAM policy and bucket policy (if cross-account) to allow access. EC2 instances and AWS services don't inherit access from being in the same account/VPC."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company is running a containerized application in ECS Fargate and needs to provide temporary AWS credentials to the container. How are credentials securely provided in Fargate?","options":["A. Set environment variables with IAM access keys in the task definition","B. Assign an ECS task IAM role — Fargate retrieves temporary credentials via the task metadata endpoint","C. Mount an EC2 instance profile — Fargate shares instance profiles with underlying EC2","D. Pass credentials via AWS Secrets Manager as environment variables at task launch"],"answer":1,"explain":"ECS task roles provide temporary credentials to Fargate containers via the task metadata endpoint (similar to EC2 instance metadata). No static credentials are needed. Fargate doesn't use EC2 instance profiles. Passing IAM credentials via Secrets Manager or environment variables creates static credential exposure risks."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company uses AWS KMS and wants to ensure that if a key is accidentally deleted, they have a recovery window. What feature provides this?","options":["A. Enable KMS key rotation — it keeps previous versions of the key","B. Schedule key deletion with a waiting period of 7–30 days — the key can be cancelled during this period","C. Enable KMS key replication to another region before deletion","D. Export the key material before deletion"],"answer":1,"explain":"KMS key deletion must be scheduled with a minimum 7-day and maximum 30-day waiting period. During this time, the deletion can be cancelled. This provides a safety net against accidental deletion. Key rotation creates new key versions but doesn't prevent deletion. Multi-region key replication requires setup before deletion. Exporting key material is only for imported key material keys."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to ensure that EC2 instances can only be accessed via AWS Systems Manager Session Manager and never via SSH. Which combination of controls enforces this?","options":["A. Remove port 22 from all security groups and ensure instances have the SSM agent with an IAM role granting ssm:StartSession","B. Deny all traffic on port 22 with Network ACLs and configure a bastion host for access","C. Enable GuardDuty SSH brute-force detection and terminate violating instances","D. Use AWS Config to detect SSH access and send SNS alerts"],"answer":0,"explain":"Removing port 22 from security groups blocks SSH at the network level. SSM Session Manager provides shell access through the SSM agent without open ports, requiring an IAM role with ssm:StartSession permission. Bastion hosts still use SSH. GuardDuty is detective, not preventive. Config alerts don't prevent access."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company using AWS Organizations needs to ensure that all accounts use AWS Config. Some accounts currently don't have it enabled. What is the most scalable way to enforce and deploy Config across all accounts?","options":["A. Manually enable Config in each account","B. Use AWS CloudFormation StackSets with service-managed permissions to deploy Config to all accounts and future accounts automatically","C. Create an SCP that requires Config to be enabled","D. Use AWS Config conformance packs — they enable Config in all accounts automatically"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFormation StackSets with service-managed permissions (Organizations integration) can deploy Config enablement across all accounts, including accounts created in the future (via automatic deployment). SCPs don't deploy resources. Conformance packs are for compliance rules, not Config enablement itself. Manual setup doesn't scale."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company stores database connection strings in EC2 user data. A security review flags this as a risk. What is the correct remediation?","options":["A. Base64-encode the connection string in user data","B. Remove connection strings from user data and retrieve them at runtime from AWS Secrets Manager or SSM Parameter Store using the instance IAM role","C. Encrypt the user data field using KMS","D. Store connection strings in S3 and download during instance launch"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 user data is accessible to any code running on the instance and is not encrypted at rest. The correct approach is to retrieve secrets at runtime from Secrets Manager or SSM Parameter Store using the instance's IAM role — the instance never stores long-term secrets. Base64 is not encryption. User data field cannot be encrypted with KMS. S3 storage without strict access controls moves but doesn't solve the problem."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company is using AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) to manage TLS certificates for their ALB. The certificate is expiring in 30 days. What happens if no action is taken?","options":["A. ACM automatically renews certificates it issued (not imported) — if domain validation is met, renewal is automatic","B. The ALB will stop serving HTTPS traffic immediately when the certificate expires","C. ACM sends an SNS notification and renews after manual approval","D. AWS extends the certificate 30 days automatically as a grace period"],"answer":0,"explain":"ACM automatically renews certificates it provisions (domain-validated or email-validated) before expiration, as long as DNS/email validation requirements are met. Imported certificates require manual renewal. The ALB will serve an expired certificate if not renewed, causing browser warnings. There is no automatic grace period extension."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company wants to audit all access to objects in an S3 bucket used for sensitive financial data. Every access, including GET requests, should be logged. Which solution provides object-level access logging?","options":["A. Enable S3 Server Access Logging to capture detailed access records including GET requests","B. Enable AWS CloudTrail S3 data events for the bucket","C. Both A and B provide object-level logging — CloudTrail Data Events is preferred for completeness and integration with other AWS services","D. Enable VPC Flow Logs for traffic to the S3 endpoint"],"answer":2,"explain":"Both S3 Server Access Logging and CloudTrail Data Events log object-level access. CloudTrail Data Events are preferred for compliance: they capture API-level detail, include requester identity, integrate with CloudWatch/SIEM, and can be queried with Athena. Server Access Logging has best-effort delivery. Using both provides maximum coverage. VPC Flow Logs don't log S3 request details."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company has a requirement that all data in transit between microservices in EKS must be encrypted. The team wants this without modifying application code. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. Configure TLS certificates manually in each microservice","B. Use AWS App Mesh with TLS enforcement between virtual nodes, using ACM Private CA for certificate management","C. Enable EKS encryption at rest — it covers transit as well","D. Use a Network Load Balancer with TLS termination between each service pair"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS App Mesh provides service mesh capabilities including automatic mTLS encryption between virtual nodes without application code changes. ACM Private CA issues and manages the certificates. EKS encryption at rest (secrets encryption) doesn't cover transit. NLB TLS termination between every service pair is operationally complex and doesn't enforce mTLS."},{"cat":"secure-arch","q":"A company needs to allow their on-premises security operations center (SOC) to query CloudTrail logs in AWS without accessing the AWS console. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. Export CloudTrail logs to S3 and provide the SOC with AWS credentials to access S3","B. Stream CloudTrail events to a CloudWatch Logs log group and create a subscription filter to ship logs to the SOC's SIEM via Kinesis Data Firehose","C. Give the SOC team root account access for CloudTrail queries","D. Run scheduled Athena queries and email results to the SOC"],"answer":1,"explain":"Streaming CloudTrail events via CloudWatch Logs subscription filter to Kinesis Data Firehose allows continuous delivery to a SIEM without AWS console access or providing static credentials. The SOC receives logs in their existing tooling. Providing S3 credentials gives persistent access requiring credential management. Root account access is a severe violation. Scheduled emails are delayed and incomplete."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs a mission-critical application on a single EC2 instance with an RDS MySQL database. They need to achieve an RTO of 15 minutes and RPO of 5 minutes. Which architecture should they implement?","options":["A. Enable RDS automated backups with 5-minute retention","B. Deploy the EC2 application in an Auto Scaling group with a minimum of 2 instances across two AZs, enable RDS Multi-AZ deployment","C. Create daily AMI snapshots of the EC2 instance and RDS snapshots","D. Use EC2 Reserved Instances and RDS Read Replicas in the same AZ"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multi-AZ RDS provides synchronous replication with automatic failover in ~1-2 minutes, meeting the 5-minute RPO. Auto Scaling group across multiple AZs replaces failed EC2 instances within minutes, meeting the 15-minute RTO. Daily snapshots have up to 24-hour RPO. Read Replicas use asynchronous replication and don't auto-failover. Reserved Instances affect cost, not availability."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's DynamoDB table receives unpredictable spikes in read traffic. The application is experiencing throttling during peak loads. What is the most cost-effective solution?","options":["A. Switch to DynamoDB provisioned capacity with maximum expected throughput","B. Enable DynamoDB on-demand capacity mode or use DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) for caching","C. Add read replicas to DynamoDB in each AZ","D. Migrate to RDS Aurora with read replicas"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB on-demand mode automatically scales to handle any traffic level without throttling, charging per request. DAX provides in-memory caching to reduce read traffic to DynamoDB. Provisioned capacity with max throughput wastes cost during low traffic. DynamoDB doesn't have traditional read replicas. Aurora migration is operationally complex for a use case DynamoDB handles natively."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"An application uses SQS for decoupling. During a processing outage, messages accumulate. After recovery, the service processes messages but some are older than the visibility timeout and are being processed multiple times. What should be implemented?","options":["A. Increase the SQS message retention period","B. Implement idempotent message processing in the consumer and configure an appropriate visibility timeout based on processing time","C. Enable SQS FIFO queues to prevent duplicate processing","D. Use SQS dead-letter queues to discard old messages"],"answer":1,"explain":"Idempotent processing ensures that processing a message multiple times produces the same result, handling the inherent at-least-once delivery of SQS standard queues. The visibility timeout should be set longer than the maximum processing time. FIFO queues provide exactly-once processing but require refactoring. DLQs handle messages that fail repeatedly, not duplicates during normal processing."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs a disaster recovery strategy for an application in us-east-1 with an RTO of 4 hours and RPO of 1 hour. They want the lowest cost DR option. Which approach is appropriate?","options":["A. Active-Active multi-region deployment","B. Warm Standby with a scaled-down environment in us-west-2 and cross-region RDS read replica","C. Pilot Light with a cross-region RDS replica and AMIs stored in us-west-2","D. Backup and Restore using S3 cross-region replication"],"answer":2,"explain":"Pilot Light maintains the minimum critical components (like a cross-region RDS replica) and pre-staged AMIs. During a disaster, you scale up from the pilot light infrastructure. With a 4-hour RTO, pilot light provides enough time to provision. Warm Standby is more expensive as it runs a scaled-down environment continuously. Active-Active is the most expensive. Backup and Restore is cheapest but typically has longer RTO than 4 hours."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application uses Amazon RDS MySQL with Multi-AZ. During a planned AZ maintenance event, a failover occurred and the application experienced a 2-minute outage. How can the team reduce this to near zero?","options":["A. Enable RDS Read Replicas in the same AZ","B. Migrate to Amazon Aurora with multiple Aurora Replicas across AZs — Aurora failover typically completes in under 30 seconds","C. Use RDS with synchronous replication and manual failover scripts","D. Deploy an RDS Proxy in front of the database to absorb connection storms"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora uses a distributed storage model with replicas. Failover to a healthy replica typically completes in under 30 seconds. RDS Proxy also helps by maintaining a connection pool so application connections don't drop during failover, but it doesn't reduce failover time itself. RDS Multi-AZ failover takes 1-2 minutes. Read Replicas in the same AZ don't help with AZ failures."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to ensure their static website on S3 is highly available globally with fast response times even if one AWS region becomes unavailable. What architecture should they deploy?","options":["A. Enable S3 Cross-Region Replication and use S3 static website URLs per region","B. Deploy CloudFront with S3 origins in multiple regions using origin groups and origin failover","C. Use Route 53 latency-based routing between two S3 static website endpoints","D. Deploy EC2 instances in multiple regions and sync content via rsync"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront origin groups support origin failover — if the primary origin (S3 in us-east-1) fails, CloudFront automatically routes to the secondary origin (S3 in another region) based on configured HTTP status code conditions. Route 53 latency routing can also work but takes longer to failover due to DNS TTL. EC2 with rsync adds operational complexity for static content."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"An application processes financial transactions and cannot afford data loss. It writes to an RDS Aurora MySQL cluster. The team wants to ensure writes are durable even if the writer instance fails. What should they configure?","options":["A. Enable Aurora backtrack to rewind to a point before the failure","B. Aurora automatically replicates data to 6 copies across 3 AZs — write durability is maintained even if the writer fails because storage is separate from compute","C. Enable RDS Multi-AZ to synchronously replicate writes to a standby","D. Configure Aurora global database for synchronous cross-region replication"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora stores data in a distributed shared storage volume with 6 copies across 3 AZs. A write is acknowledged when 4 of 6 copies confirm the write. Even if the writer instance fails, the storage data is intact. Aurora global databases use asynchronous replication. Backtrack is a point-in-time recovery feature, not a durability mechanism. RDS Multi-AZ (non-Aurora) achieves similar durability but Aurora is the correct answer here."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's microservices use synchronous HTTP calls between services. During high load, slow downstream services cause a cascade of failures across the entire system. What pattern resolves this?","options":["A. Increase EC2 instance sizes for all services","B. Implement circuit breaker pattern using AWS App Mesh or Amazon API Gateway with timeouts, retries, and request throttling between services","C. Use CloudFront to cache inter-service calls","D. Move to a monolithic architecture to reduce inter-service latency"],"answer":1,"explain":"Circuit breakers prevent cascade failures by stopping requests to a failing service and returning fast failures or fallback responses. App Mesh provides this at the service mesh layer. API Gateway with timeouts and throttling provides similar protection. Simply scaling instances doesn't prevent cascades from slow services. CloudFront doesn't help with internal service-to-service calls."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs to process streaming data from IoT devices with no data loss, even during peak loads. The processing Lambda function sometimes fails. What architecture ensures reliability?","options":["A. API Gateway → Lambda with no retry","B. Kinesis Data Streams → Lambda event source mapping with bisect-on-error and DLQ for failed records","C. SQS → Lambda with a 30-second visibility timeout","D. Direct IoT device to Lambda invocation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Data Streams with Lambda event source mapping retries failed batches. Enabling BisectOnFunctionError splits failing batches to isolate problematic records. A DLQ captures records that fail after all retries. This ensures no data loss. SQS can also work but Kinesis is designed for ordered streaming data from IoT. Direct Lambda invocation from IoT without a buffer is not resilient to Lambda throttling."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's Route 53 DNS points to an Application Load Balancer in us-east-1. They want automatic failover to an ALB in us-west-2 if the primary region becomes unavailable. What Route 53 configuration achieves this?","options":["A. Create A records with equal weights for both ALBs","B. Configure Route 53 Failover routing with health checks on both ALBs — primary in us-east-1, secondary in us-west-2","C. Use Route 53 latency routing to route to the fastest region","D. Enable Route 53 Resolver failover rules"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 Failover routing with associated health checks automatically routes traffic to the secondary record when the primary health check fails. Health checks monitor the ALB endpoint. Weighted routing distributes traffic to both but doesn't stop sending to a failed region. Latency routing optimizes for speed, not failover. Resolver rules are for DNS resolution within VPCs."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs an ECS Fargate application with a single task definition. During deployments, there is a brief downtime as old tasks stop before new ones start. How can they achieve zero-downtime deployments?","options":["A. Use ECS rolling updates with minimum healthy percent 100 and maximum percent 200","B. Deploy new tasks manually before stopping old ones using a custom script","C. Use blue/green deployments via AWS CodeDeploy with an ALB target group swap","D. Both A and C are valid zero-downtime deployment strategies"],"answer":3,"explain":"Both approaches achieve zero downtime. ECS rolling update with min 100%/max 200% keeps all current tasks running while adding new tasks before removing old ones. Blue/green with CodeDeploy shifts traffic between target groups after validation, with instant rollback capability. Choice depends on whether instant rollback or gradual traffic shifting is preferred."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"An application stores session state on individual EC2 instances behind an ALB. When an instance is replaced by Auto Scaling, users lose their sessions. What is the recommended fix?","options":["A. Enable ALB sticky sessions (session affinity)","B. Move session state to Amazon ElastiCache for Redis, which is accessible by all instances","C. Use EC2 instance store for session data with more frequent backups","D. Increase the Auto Scaling minimum instance count to prevent replacements"],"answer":1,"explain":"Externalizing session state to ElastiCache for Redis makes sessions available to all instances. If an instance fails or is replaced, users can continue their session on any other instance. Sticky sessions route users to the same instance but fail if that instance is terminated. Instance store data is lost on termination. Preventing scale-in reduces cost efficiency."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company has a Lambda function that calls an external API. The external API occasionally times out. The team wants the function to retry with exponential backoff without blocking other invocations. What is the best approach?","options":["A. Use synchronous Lambda invocations with retry logic in the calling application","B. Configure Lambda destination for failures and use SQS for retry with exponential backoff via Lambda event source mapping redrive policy","C. Wrap the API call in a try/catch and sleep between retries inside the Lambda function","D. Use Step Functions to orchestrate the Lambda with Wait states for exponential backoff between retries"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Step Functions can implement retry logic with exponential backoff, max attempts, and jitter using the Retry field in state machine tasks — without blocking Lambda invocations. Sleeping inside Lambda wastes compute time and cost. SQS with redrive works for async patterns but adds queue latency. Synchronous retries in the calling app couple the caller to the retry logic."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs a three-tier web application. The database tier uses RDS MySQL. The middle tier uses EC2 in an Auto Scaling group. They want the middle tier to be resilient to AZ failures. What changes are needed?","options":["A. Deploy the Auto Scaling group with instances in a single AZ with more instances","B. Configure the Auto Scaling group to span multiple AZs and use an ALB across the same AZs","C. Use EC2 placement groups with spread strategy in a single AZ","D. Deploy multiple Auto Scaling groups, one per AZ, with manual traffic distribution"],"answer":1,"explain":"Deploying an Auto Scaling group across multiple AZs with an ALB ensures that if one AZ fails, instances in other AZs continue serving traffic. Auto Scaling automatically replaces instances and maintains capacity across healthy AZs. Spread placement groups reduce instance failure impact within an AZ but don't protect against AZ failure. Single AZ with more instances fails entirely if the AZ goes down."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A financial application requires that messages be processed exactly once and in order. What AWS messaging solution should be used?","options":["A. Amazon SQS Standard queue","B. Amazon SQS FIFO queue with message deduplication enabled","C. Amazon SNS with SQS fan-out","D. Amazon Kinesis Data Streams with enhanced fan-out"],"answer":1,"explain":"SQS FIFO queues guarantee exactly-once processing (using deduplication IDs) and first-in-first-out ordering within a message group. Standard SQS offers at-least-once delivery and best-effort ordering. SNS fan-out doesn't guarantee ordering. Kinesis provides ordered records per shard but delivers at-least-once, requiring application-level deduplication."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application in us-east-1 uses DynamoDB. They need a globally available database with reads and writes accepted in both us-east-1 and eu-west-1 with conflict resolution. What should they configure?","options":["A. Enable DynamoDB Cross-Region Replication with active-passive configuration","B. Enable DynamoDB Global Tables with tables in both regions — it provides active-active replication with last-writer-wins conflict resolution","C. Create DynamoDB tables in both regions and handle replication with Lambda","D. Use Aurora Global Database with write forwarding enabled"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB Global Tables provide fully managed active-active multi-region replication. Both regions accept reads and writes, with last-writer-wins conflict resolution based on timestamps. Cross-region DynamoDB replication is not a native feature without Global Tables. Lambda-based replication is operational overhead. Aurora is a relational database, not DynamoDB."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's architecture has a downstream service that occasionally returns 500 errors and slow responses. The upstream service needs to handle this gracefully without failing. What architecture pattern should be applied?","options":["A. Retry the request indefinitely until it succeeds","B. Implement timeouts, retries with exponential backoff and jitter, and a circuit breaker that opens after consecutive failures","C. Queue all requests in SQS and let the downstream service process when available","D. Increase Lambda concurrency limits on the downstream service"],"answer":1,"explain":"Resilient service-to-service calls should use timeouts (don't wait indefinitely), exponential backoff with jitter (avoid thundering herd on retry), and circuit breakers (stop calling a failing service, allow time to recover). Indefinite retries exacerbate the problem. SQS decoupling is a valid pattern but changes the architecture to async. Increasing concurrency addresses capacity, not failure handling."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's ECS cluster runs stateless microservices. They want to maximize availability during an underlying EC2 instance failure. Which placement strategy achieves the best distribution of tasks?","options":["A. Use the 'binpack' placement strategy to consolidate tasks on fewer instances","B. Use the 'spread' placement strategy across both AZ and instanceId to distribute tasks across instances and AZs","C. Use the 'random' placement strategy","D. Use a single large instance with multiple tasks"],"answer":1,"explain":"ECS spread placement strategy distributes tasks evenly across specified attributes. Spreading first by AZ then by instanceId ensures maximum distribution — tasks are spread across AZs first, then across individual instances within AZs. Binpack consolidates tasks, maximizing cost efficiency but reducing fault tolerance. Random is unpredictable. Single instance is a single point of failure."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs a batch processing workload that takes 6 hours to complete. The workload uses EC2 Spot Instances to save costs. How should they design the job to handle Spot interruptions?","options":["A. Use Spot Instances with On-Demand as backup — no code changes needed","B. Implement checkpointing to save progress to S3 or DynamoDB, and use Spot interruption notices (2-minute warning) to save state before termination","C. Run the job on a single large On-Demand instance to avoid interruptions","D. Use SQS to queue each 6-hour batch job and retry if interrupted"],"answer":1,"explain":"Spot Instances provide a 2-minute interruption notice via EC2 instance metadata. The application should save its progress (checkpoint) periodically and on receiving the interruption notice. After a replacement Spot Instance starts, it resumes from the last checkpoint. This avoids restarting from scratch. Spot with On-Demand backup (Spot Fleet) helps with availability but without checkpointing, interrupted jobs restart from scratch."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants their application to continue operating in read-only mode during a database outage. Currently, all reads go to the primary RDS instance. What architecture change enables this?","options":["A. Enable RDS Multi-AZ — the standby handles reads during primary failure","B. Create RDS Read Replicas and update the application to direct read queries to replicas — during primary failure, reads continue from replicas","C. Enable RDS automated backups to restore quickly","D. Use Amazon ElastiCache to cache all reads — the application serves from cache during RDS failure"],"answer":3,"explain":"ElastiCache caches database reads. During an RDS failure, the application can continue serving cached data (read-only mode) without hitting the database. RDS Read Replicas enable read scaling but replicas also fail if they depend on the primary for replication. Multi-AZ standby is not readable. The question asks for read-only mode during an outage — cache is the most resilient approach."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's serverless application uses Lambda and DynamoDB. Lambda functions sometimes fail due to downstream API timeouts. The team wants to retry failed Lambda invocations automatically. What should they configure?","options":["A. Set Lambda retry attempts to 0 and handle retries in the calling code","B. For asynchronous Lambda invocations, configure the retry attempts (up to 2) and configure a Dead Letter Queue (SQS or SNS) for failed events after all retries","C. Use Lambda provisioned concurrency to prevent timeouts","D. Increase the Lambda function timeout to 15 minutes to wait for slow APIs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Async Lambda invocations support up to 2 retry attempts with delays between retries. A DLQ captures events that fail after all retry attempts for analysis or manual reprocessing. Provisioned concurrency prevents cold starts but doesn't help with downstream timeouts. Increasing timeout wastes compute cost waiting for a potentially unavailable API. Suppressing retries loses data."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon SQS to decouple their order processing system. During a major sale, the queue depth grows to 1 million messages and processing falls behind. What is the most cost-effective way to scale processing?","options":["A. Manually add more EC2 instances to the processing tier","B. Use Auto Scaling based on the ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible SQS metric to scale EC2 or Lambda consumers automatically","C. Increase the SQS message retention period to 14 days","D. Use SQS FIFO to process messages faster"],"answer":1,"explain":"Auto Scaling using the ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible metric allows the consumer fleet to scale automatically with queue depth. Lambda with SQS event source mapping scales automatically up to concurrency limits. Manual scaling reacts too slowly. Message retention affects how long messages stay in queue, not processing speed. FIFO queues have lower throughput than Standard queues."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs a critical API on EC2 instances. An ALB health check fails when the application is under heavy load, causing healthy instances to be terminated by Auto Scaling. How should they address this?","options":["A. Disable ALB health checks during peak periods","B. Tune the ALB health check thresholds (increase healthy/unhealthy threshold counts and interval), and configure a separate lightweight health check endpoint that doesn't perform heavy operations","C. Increase the EC2 instance size to handle the heavy load","D. Switch from ALB to NLB — NLB health checks are less sensitive"],"answer":1,"explain":"Creating a lightweight health check endpoint (e.g., returns HTTP 200 with no database calls) ensures health checks succeed even under load. Tuning thresholds reduces false positives from momentary slowness. Disabling health checks removes protection against actual failures. Larger instances may still fail under extreme load. NLB health checks are at Layer 4 and don't solve application-level health check accuracy."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application writes to S3 and requires that writes be confirmed before proceeding. A downstream Lambda function processes S3 objects as they arrive. Objects are sometimes processed before the write is fully committed, resulting in empty reads. What is the root cause and fix?","options":["A. S3 has eventual consistency for all write operations — add a delay before Lambda reads","B. This was previously a limitation but S3 now provides strong consistency for all operations — ensure the Lambda is using the correct S3 GetObject API and is not reading stale cached data","C. Use S3 Versioning to ensure Lambda always reads the latest version","D. Switch to EFS for strongly consistent file writes"],"answer":1,"explain":"As of December 2020, Amazon S3 provides strong read-after-write consistency for all operations including PUTs of new objects and overwrites. If Lambda reads an empty object after an S3 event trigger, the issue is likely a race condition in the application logic or a caching/configuration issue, not S3 consistency. Delays are unnecessary. Versioning helps with overwrites but not the fundamental issue described."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs to implement a blue/green deployment for their RDS database schema changes. What is the recommended AWS approach?","options":["A. Create a new RDS instance (green), apply schema changes, switch the application's connection string, and decommission the old instance (blue)","B. Use RDS Blue/Green Deployments feature to create a green environment, apply changes, and switch over with minimal downtime","C. Use RDS Read Replicas as the green environment and promote after schema changes","D. Apply schema changes directly to production after creating a manual snapshot"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Blue/Green Deployments is a native AWS feature that creates a staging environment (green) synchronized with production (blue) using logical replication. You can apply and test schema changes on green, then switch over with minimal downtime. Switchover is managed by RDS. Manual green deployments are complex. Read Replica promotion doesn't support rollback to blue. Direct production changes are risky."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application uses AWS Lambda and experienced a sharp increase in errors during a deployment of new code. How can they minimize impact of future bad deployments?","options":["A. Always deploy Lambda functions manually one at a time","B. Use Lambda aliases with weighted routing (canary deployments) — route a small percentage of traffic to the new version and monitor for errors before full deployment","C. Increase Lambda memory to prevent errors","D. Use Lambda layers to deploy code separately from configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda aliases support traffic shifting — you can route a percentage of requests to the new version (canary) while monitoring CloudWatch metrics for error rates. If errors increase, roll back immediately to the previous version. Full cutover happens only after validation. Manual deployments don't scale. Memory increases don't prevent code errors. Layers separate dependencies, not traffic routing."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to run a web application that automatically scales to handle traffic spikes while maintaining a consistent cost base. Which combination achieves this?","options":["A. EC2 Spot Instances with Auto Scaling only","B. A mix of On-Demand or Reserved Instances for baseline capacity and Spot Instances for burst capacity in an Auto Scaling group with a mixed instance policy","C. EC2 On-Demand Instances with manual scaling","D. ECS Fargate with fixed task count and step scaling"],"answer":1,"explain":"A mixed instance policy Auto Scaling group uses On-Demand/Reserved Instances for the steady baseline (predictable cost and availability) and Spot Instances for burst (up to 90% cheaper). If Spot capacity is unavailable, On-Demand handles the load. Pure Spot is unreliable for critical workloads. Manual scaling can't respond to rapid spikes. Fargate with step scaling works but doesn't optimize cost as effectively."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's multi-tier application uses EC2, RDS, and ElastiCache. All resources are in a single AZ. A storm causes the AZ to lose power. They want to recover within 30 minutes. What is the minimum architecture change?","options":["A. Enable RDS automated backups and EC2 AMI snapshots","B. Enable RDS Multi-AZ, deploy EC2 in an Auto Scaling group across 2+ AZs, and ensure ElastiCache uses Multi-AZ replication groups","C. Replicate everything to a second region with Route 53 failover","D. Enable CloudFront caching to serve content during the outage"],"answer":1,"explain":"Deploying across multiple AZs within the same region provides resilience against single-AZ failures. RDS Multi-AZ automatic failover, EC2 Auto Scaling across AZs, and ElastiCache Multi-AZ replication groups all recover within minutes of an AZ failure. Cross-region replication meets the 30-minute RTO but adds significant cost and complexity. Snapshots enable recovery but typically exceed 30-minute RTO. CloudFront caches content but not application state."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application sends emails via Amazon SES. Occasionally SES returns throttling errors and emails are dropped. How should they make email sending resilient?","options":["A. Retry SES calls immediately on error in the application code","B. Place email send requests in an SQS queue and process with a Lambda function that handles SES throttling errors with exponential backoff","C. Use SNS instead of SES for email delivery","D. Increase the SES sending quota and no further changes are needed"],"answer":1,"explain":"An SQS-based buffer decouples email generation from SES delivery. The Lambda consumer retries with exponential backoff when SES returns throttling errors, ensuring no emails are dropped. Direct in-line retries block the calling thread. SNS sends notifications, not transactional emails via SES. Increasing quota helps but doesn't handle transient throttling gracefully."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses an Application Load Balancer with EC2 instances. Occasionally, a single instance becomes unhealthy due to memory leak but takes 5 minutes to be detected and removed by the ALB. Users receive errors during this window. How can the detection time be reduced?","options":["A. Increase the number of EC2 instances to dilute traffic to the unhealthy instance","B. Tune ALB health check settings: reduce the check interval to 10 seconds and unhealthy threshold to 2, ensuring the instance is removed within ~20 seconds of becoming unhealthy","C. Use NLB instead of ALB for faster health checks","D. Enable Auto Scaling with a 5-minute cooldown period"],"answer":1,"explain":"The default ALB health check interval is 30 seconds with an unhealthy threshold of 2-3. Reducing the interval to 10 seconds and threshold to 2 means an instance is removed within ~20 seconds (2 x 10s) of failing health checks. NLB health checks also support tuning but ALB provides better application-layer health checking. More instances dilute errors but don't accelerate detection."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to ensure their S3-hosted data is protected against accidental deletion by any user, including administrators. Which feature prevents this?","options":["A. Enable S3 versioning — it moves deleted objects to a delete marker","B. Enable S3 Object Lock with COMPLIANCE mode and a retention period — prevents deletion even by the root account","C. Apply a bucket policy denying DeleteObject for IAM users","D. Enable MFA Delete on the S3 bucket"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Object Lock COMPLIANCE mode prevents object deletion or modification until the retention period expires — no user, including root, can override this. MFA Delete requires MFA for deletions but can be disabled by the root account. Bucket policies denying DeleteObject can be overridden by the account administrator. Versioning creates delete markers but objects can still be permanently deleted by deleting all versions."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's Lambda functions are experiencing cold starts affecting user experience. The functions are invoked unpredictably with occasional bursts. What is the most effective mitigation?","options":["A. Increase Lambda function memory allocation","B. Enable Lambda Provisioned Concurrency for the most latency-sensitive functions","C. Package the Lambda function as a container image","D. Use a larger deployment package to avoid cold start initialization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda Provisioned Concurrency keeps a specified number of execution environments initialized and ready to respond with no cold start. This is the most effective solution for latency-sensitive functions. Increasing memory can reduce cold start duration slightly but doesn't eliminate it. Container images increase cold start times. Larger packages actually increase cold start time due to more code to initialize."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Aurora. They need to ensure their reporting queries don't impact the transactional workload performance. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. Schedule reports to run during off-peak hours on the primary instance","B. Create Aurora Read Replicas and direct reporting queries to the reader endpoint","C. Increase the Aurora writer instance size","D. Use Aurora Serverless for the reporting workload"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora Read Replicas share the same distributed storage as the writer but handle read traffic independently. The Aurora reader endpoint automatically load balances reads across all replicas. This offloads reporting query load from the writer. Scheduling doesn't prevent contention if the workload overlaps. Increasing writer size doesn't prevent resource contention. Aurora Serverless v2 is appropriate for unpredictable workloads, not isolated reporting."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company experiences database connection exhaustion during traffic spikes because their Lambda functions each open a new connection. The RDS max_connections limit is being hit. What resolves this?","options":["A. Increase RDS instance size to support more connections","B. Deploy Amazon RDS Proxy in front of RDS — it pools and reuses database connections, reducing the connection count by multiplexing Lambda connections","C. Reduce Lambda concurrency limits","D. Use DynamoDB instead of RDS to avoid connection limits"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Proxy maintains a pool of database connections and multiplexes them across many Lambda function invocations. Instead of each Lambda invocation opening a new connection, they reuse pooled connections. This can reduce connection count by 99% in Lambda-heavy workloads. Larger RDS instances support more connections but it's still a finite limit. Reducing Lambda concurrency impacts throughput. DynamoDB migration is a major architectural change."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company has a microservices architecture where Service A calls Service B. Service B has a rolling deployment happening and some requests fail during the rollout. How can the client (Service A) handle these failures without user impact?","options":["A. Delay Service A deployments until Service B deployment is complete","B. Implement retry logic with exponential backoff in Service A, and ensure the ALB health checks for Service B quickly detect and remove unhealthy instances during deployment","C. Use a database flag to indicate when Service B is in deployment mode","D. Deploy Service B only during maintenance windows with 0 traffic"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client-side retry logic handles transient failures during deployments. Combined with tuned ALB health checks that quickly remove instances serving errors, the window of retried requests is minimized. Coordinating deployment windows doesn't work in a continuous deployment culture. Deployment flags require application changes to both services. Maintenance windows reduce availability."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's API Gateway triggers a Lambda function. During load testing, Lambda reaches its concurrency limit and returns 429 errors to clients. What should the architect recommend?","options":["A. Enable API Gateway caching to reduce Lambda invocations","B. Request a Lambda concurrency limit increase from AWS, configure reserved concurrency for critical functions, and implement SQS buffering for non-latency-sensitive operations","C. Migrate from Lambda to EC2 to avoid concurrency limits","D. Use API Gateway throttling to queue all requests above the concurrency limit"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda reserved concurrency ensures critical functions always have capacity. For burst capacity, request limit increases. For non-real-time APIs, an SQS queue buffers requests and Lambda processes at its pace without 429 errors. API Gateway caching reduces calls but doesn't solve the concurrency issue for all workloads. EC2 migration is unnecessary. API Gateway throttling returns 429s, which is what they're trying to avoid."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company stores critical application data in an S3 bucket. They want to recover from accidental overwrites of specific objects. Which feature enables recovery of overwritten S3 objects?","options":["A. S3 Cross-Region Replication","B. S3 Versioning — each overwrite creates a new version, and previous versions can be restored","C. S3 Lifecycle policies","D. S3 Object Lock"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Versioning maintains all versions of every object. An accidental overwrite creates a new version while preserving the previous version, which can be restored by retrieving the previous version ID. Cross-Region Replication replicates to another region but also replicates overwrites. Lifecycle policies manage object expiration. Object Lock prevents deletion/modification but doesn't help with restoring from overwrites."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to ensure their application can handle a database failover with no manual intervention required. The application currently uses a hardcoded RDS primary endpoint. What should be changed?","options":["A. Switch to using the RDS Multi-AZ instance endpoint — it automatically points to the new primary after failover","B. Use the RDS cluster endpoint for Aurora or the standard endpoint for RDS Multi-AZ — these automatically resolve to the current primary after failover","C. Update DNS records manually after each failover","D. Use an Elastic IP for the RDS instance to maintain a consistent endpoint"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Multi-AZ endpoints (the standard instance endpoint, not a read replica endpoint) automatically resolve to the current primary after a failover — DNS is updated by RDS within 1-2 minutes. Aurora cluster endpoints work the same way. Hardcoded IP or manual DNS updates require human intervention. Elastic IPs are for EC2, not RDS."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Elastic Beanstalk for a web application. They want to update the application with zero downtime and the ability to instantly roll back. Which deployment policy should they use?","options":["A. All at once deployment","B. Immutable deployment or Blue/Green via Elastic Beanstalk environment swap","C. Rolling deployment with batch size 25%","D. Rolling with additional batch"],"answer":1,"explain":"Immutable deployment creates new instances with the new version. If the deployment fails, the new instances are discarded (instant rollback, no downtime). Blue/Green swaps traffic between two full environments with instant URL swap and rollback. All at once causes brief downtime. Rolling and Rolling with additional batch cause partial downtime during replacement."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs a 24/7 e-commerce platform. They must maintain availability during a region-wide AWS outage. Which architecture pattern achieves this?","options":["A. Multi-AZ deployment in the primary region","B. Active-Active multi-region deployment with Route 53 health checks and data replicated between regions","C. Daily cross-region AMI copy with a recovery runbook","D. AWS Outposts for on-premises redundancy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Active-Active multi-region deployment means both regions actively serve traffic. Route 53 health checks detect a region failure and stop routing to it. Data is replicated between regions (e.g., Aurora Global Database, DynamoDB Global Tables). This provides the highest availability against region-wide outages. Multi-AZ only protects against AZ failures. AMI copies enable recovery but require manual steps with longer RTO. Outposts bring AWS to on-premises but don't protect against a region-wide failure."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application uses Amazon SNS to fan out to 5 SQS queues. One downstream processing service is slow and its SQS queue is growing. How does this affect the other queues?","options":["A. SNS slows down delivery to all queues when one queue is slow","B. Each SQS queue is independent — a slow consumer on one queue does not affect delivery or processing of other queues","C. SNS applies backpressure and all subscribed queues receive messages at the slowest consumer's rate","D. SNS will drop messages to the slow queue and redistribute to other queues"],"answer":1,"explain":"SNS fan-out delivers messages independently to each subscribed SQS queue. Each SQS queue has its own message retention, visibility timeout, and consumer processing rate. A slow consumer causes message accumulation in its queue but has no effect on other queues' delivery or processing. SNS doesn't throttle based on consumer speed."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Step Functions to orchestrate a long-running workflow. A task in the middle of the workflow sometimes fails due to a transient error in a downstream service. How should they handle this?","options":["A. Restart the entire workflow from the beginning on any failure","B. Configure Retry policies on the failing task state with exponential backoff and MaxAttempts, and a Catch block to handle persistent failures gracefully","C. Set the entire workflow's timeout to 0 to fail fast","D. Use a Lambda function inside the task to implement retry logic"],"answer":1,"explain":"Step Functions state machines support per-state Retry configuration with ErrorEquals, IntervalSeconds, MaxAttempts, and BackoffRate fields for exponential backoff. A Catch block routes the workflow to a failure handling state if all retries fail. Restarting the entire workflow wastes completed work. Task-level retries in Step Functions are cleaner than in-Lambda retries for orchestration concerns."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's EC2-based application in a VPC needs to call an external weather API over the internet. The instances are in private subnets. What provides internet access for the private instances with high availability?","options":["A. Attach an internet gateway directly to the private subnet","B. Deploy NAT Gateways in multiple public subnets (one per AZ) and configure private subnet route tables to use the NAT Gateway in the same AZ","C. Deploy a single NAT Gateway in one public subnet and route all private subnets to it","D. Assign public IPs to all EC2 instances in the private subnets"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Gateways in each AZ provide HA for outbound internet access. If one AZ's NAT Gateway fails, instances in other AZs use their own AZ's NAT Gateway. A single NAT Gateway is a single point of failure for all AZs. Internet gateway attached to private subnets makes them public subnets. Assigning public IPs exposes instances directly to the internet."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. A shard is receiving more data than it can handle (exceeding 1 MB/s or 1000 records/s). What should the architect do?","options":["A. Increase the Kinesis record retention period","B. Reshard the stream by splitting the hot shard into two shards to double the capacity for that partition","C. Enable Kinesis Enhanced Fan-Out for the affected consumers","D. Compress records before writing to reduce the data size below the shard limit"],"answer":1,"explain":"When a shard is hot (exceeding its limits), splitting it doubles the capacity for that partition. The hot shard is split based on the hash key range. Enhanced Fan-Out increases consumer read throughput (2 MB/s per consumer per shard) but doesn't increase write capacity. Compression helps if the bottleneck is data size, but record count limits (1000/s) would still apply. Retention period affects how long data is available, not throughput."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to implement automated failover for their on-premises primary data center to AWS. The connection to AWS is through Direct Connect. If Direct Connect fails, how can they maintain connectivity?","options":["A. Configure a second Direct Connect connection as the only backup","B. Configure a Site-to-Site VPN as a backup path over the internet, with BGP route preferences favoring Direct Connect when available","C. Use AWS CloudFront as a fallback for Direct Connect failures","D. Use VPC peering to route around the Direct Connect failure"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS recommends a Site-to-Site VPN as backup for Direct Connect failures. BGP can be used to set lower preference (higher metric) on the VPN path, ensuring Direct Connect is preferred when available and automatic failover to VPN when Direct Connect fails. A second Direct Connect increases availability but shares risk factors (same ISP or carrier path). CloudFront and VPC peering don't address on-premises connectivity."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application uses AWS SQS. Messages must not be lost if processing fails. After 3 failed processing attempts, messages should be preserved for manual review. What configuration achieves this?","options":["A. Set the message retention period to 14 days","B. Configure a Dead Letter Queue (DLQ) with maxReceiveCount set to 3 — after 3 failed processing attempts, messages are moved to the DLQ","C. Enable SQS FIFO to track message delivery status","D. Use SNS with SQS subscription and set SNS retry policy to 3 attempts"],"answer":1,"explain":"A DLQ with maxReceiveCount=3 moves messages to the DLQ after 3 processing failures, preserving them for analysis and reprocessing. The DLQ has its own retention period (up to 14 days). Retention period keeps messages in the main queue longer but doesn't separate failed messages. FIFO provides ordering, not failure tracking. SNS retries are for delivery, not processing failures."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs to migrate an on-premises Oracle database to AWS with zero data loss and minimal downtime. Which AWS service facilitates this migration?","options":["A. AWS Snowball for offline database export","B. AWS Database Migration Service (DMS) with Oracle as source and Aurora PostgreSQL as target, using continuous replication for cut-over","C. RDS Oracle Multi-AZ as target with manual export/import","D. AWS DataSync for database file transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS DMS supports continuous replication (CDC) from Oracle to Aurora PostgreSQL. The initial full load copies existing data, then ongoing CDC replicates changes. Cut-over happens when both databases are in sync, minimizing downtime and ensuring zero data loss during migration. Snowball is for offline bulk migration with data loss during transit. Manual export/import requires extended downtime. DataSync is for file/object storage, not databases."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company has a distributed application across multiple AWS regions. They use Route 53 for DNS. They want to ensure users are always routed to the closest healthy region. What Route 53 routing policy should be configured?","options":["A. Weighted routing with equal weights across regions","B. Latency-based routing with health checks on each regional endpoint","C. Geolocation routing based on user country","D. Simple routing with TTL set to 1 second"],"answer":1,"explain":"Latency-based routing with health checks routes users to the lowest-latency healthy region. If the closest region fails health checks, Route 53 automatically routes to the next lowest-latency healthy region. Weighted routing distributes by percentage, not proximity. Geolocation routing is based on geography (country/continent), not latency. Simple routing doesn't support health checks or multi-region failover."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company experiences periodic spikes in traffic to their application every day at 9 AM when employees log in. The Auto Scaling group takes 10 minutes to scale up, causing poor user experience during the spike. What is the best solution?","options":["A. Permanently run more instances to handle the peak","B. Configure a scheduled scaling action to increase capacity before 9 AM, combined with dynamic scaling to handle unexpected spikes","C. Increase the Auto Scaling cooldown period to prevent thrashing","D. Use EC2 Spot Instances to quickly provision extra capacity at 9 AM"],"answer":1,"explain":"Scheduled scaling proactively adds capacity before the known spike at 9 AM (e.g., scale out at 8:45 AM). Dynamic scaling (target tracking or step scaling) handles unexpected spikes throughout the day. Running excess instances 24/7 wastes cost. Cooldown periods slow down scaling, making the problem worse. Spot Instances save cost but don't address the 10-minute provisioning lag."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's web application experiences a large number of unique session reads from ElastiCache. Cache hit rate is below 50%. What architectural change would improve this?","options":["A. Increase ElastiCache node size","B. Review the cache key design — ensure objects are being cached effectively, consider increasing TTL for frequently accessed, infrequently changed data, and evaluate whether lazy loading or write-through caching is appropriate","C. Replicate ElastiCache to multiple AZs","D. Switch from ElastiCache Redis to ElastiCache Memcached for better hit rates"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cache hit rate below 50% usually indicates poor cache key design, TTL too short, or data being evicted too quickly. Reviewing caching strategy (lazy loading vs. write-through) and TTL values for read patterns typically resolves this. Larger nodes help with eviction due to memory pressure but don't address key design issues. Multi-AZ replication is for HA, not hit rate. Redis vs. Memcached doesn't inherently improve hit rates."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs their production RDS database to be protected from accidental deletion by CloudFormation stack updates or deletions. What is the recommended protection?","options":["A. Enable RDS automated backups with a 35-day retention period","B. Enable the DeletionPolicy: Retain and UpdateReplacePolicy: Retain in the CloudFormation resource, and enable RDS deletion protection","C. Use a CloudFormation StackSet to prevent stack deletion","D. Set the CloudFormation termination protection on the stack"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFormation DeletionPolicy: Retain ensures the RDS instance is not deleted when the stack or resource is deleted. UpdateReplacePolicy: Retain prevents replacement during updates. RDS deletion protection also prevents deletion via the API or console. Stack termination protection prevents the entire stack from being deleted but is overridable by administrators. Automated backups enable recovery after deletion but don't prevent it."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs a mobile application backend. During marketing campaigns, traffic can increase 10x unexpectedly. The backend uses API Gateway and Lambda. What architecture characteristics make this resilient to sudden scaling?","options":["A. Lambda's automatic scaling from 0 to thousands of concurrent executions, API Gateway's ability to handle millions of requests per second, and DynamoDB on-demand capacity absorb traffic spikes without pre-provisioning","B. Reserved EC2 capacity ensures consistent performance during spikes","C. CloudFront caching handles all Lambda invocations during spikes","D. SQS buffers API Gateway requests and Lambda processes at a fixed rate"],"answer":0,"explain":"Lambda + API Gateway + DynamoDB on-demand is inherently serverless and scales automatically with demand. Lambda scales to thousands of concurrent executions, API Gateway handles massive RPS, and DynamoDB on-demand scales with traffic. This combination handles 10x spikes without pre-provisioning. Reserved EC2 requires pre-sizing. CloudFront caches static content but not all API responses. SQS buffering converts synchronous to async, changing the application model."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application uses an ALB with multiple target groups. They want canary testing where 5% of traffic goes to a new version. Which ALB feature enables this?","options":["A. ALB sticky sessions","B. ALB weighted target groups — assign 95% weight to the stable target group and 5% to the canary target group","C. ALB path-based routing rules","D. ALB host-based routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"ALB weighted target groups allow splitting traffic by percentage between target groups on the same listener rule. Set weight 95 for stable and 5 for canary. Sticky sessions pin users to specific targets, not traffic splitting. Path-based and host-based routing are for routing different URL paths or hostnames, not traffic splitting."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs to architect a solution that can recover an entire AWS environment in a new region within 1 hour of a disaster declaration. What enables this?","options":["A. Maintain warm standby with all resources running at reduced capacity in the DR region","B. Use infrastructure as code (CloudFormation/Terraform) with cross-region AMI copies, RDS cross-region snapshots, and automated deployment pipelines that can recreate the environment on-demand","C. Store manual runbooks for the operations team to follow during disaster recovery","D. Use AWS Backup with cross-region copy jobs for all resources"],"answer":1,"explain":"IaC enables rapid, automated environment recreation in any region. Pre-copied AMIs and RDS snapshots in the target region eliminate data transfer time during recovery. Automated pipelines can deploy the full stack within an hour. Warm standby costs more but recovers faster. Manual runbooks are error-prone and slower than automation. AWS Backup handles data but not infrastructure provisioning."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's application writes large files to Amazon EFS. When the EFS mount target in one AZ becomes unavailable, applications in that AZ lose access to files. How can they improve EFS resilience?","options":["A. Enable EFS replication to a second EFS file system in another region","B. Ensure the application mounts EFS using the DNS name which automatically routes to an available mount target — deploy mount targets in all AZs used by the application","C. Use EBS instead of EFS for shared file storage","D. Set up S3 as a cache in front of EFS"],"answer":1,"explain":"EFS mount targets should be created in each AZ where application instances run. When mounting using the DNS name (fs-xxxx.efs.region.amazonaws.com), EFS automatically resolves to a mount target in the same AZ. If one mount target fails, only instances in that AZ are affected — other AZ instances continue normally. EFS replication creates a read-only replica. EBS is not shared across instances."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company processes medical imaging data with large batch jobs on EC2 Spot Instances. A Spot interruption causes the batch job to fail after 5 hours of processing. What design change minimizes reprocessing?","options":["A. Switch to On-Demand Instances for all batch processing","B. Implement job checkpointing every 30 minutes, saving progress to S3, so interrupted jobs resume from the last checkpoint rather than restarting from scratch","C. Use Amazon Batch which automatically handles Spot interruptions","D. Use Amazon EMR Spot with checkpointing disabled"],"answer":1,"explain":"Checkpointing to S3 every 30 minutes limits potential reprocessing to 30 minutes of work after a Spot interruption. Without checkpointing, the full 5 hours of work is lost. On-Demand is more expensive and doesn't address workflow design. AWS Batch manages Spot interruptions by re-queuing the job but still starts it from the beginning without checkpointing. EMR Spot is for distributed data processing frameworks."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Aurora Serverless v2 for their application. They want to ensure the database can handle sudden spikes from 1 to 100 ACU without any user impact. What should they configure?","options":["A. Set the minimum capacity to 1 ACU and maximum to 128 ACU — Aurora Serverless v2 scales smoothly between these values in seconds","B. Pre-warm the Aurora cluster by running load tests before each expected spike","C. Use Aurora Serverless v1 for better spike handling","D. Set provisioned capacity at 100 ACU to always be ready"],"answer":0,"explain":"Aurora Serverless v2 scales capacity in fine-grained increments (as small as 0.5 ACU) and can scale from minimum to maximum in seconds, handling sudden spikes transparently. Setting max to 128 ACU (or higher) ensures capacity is available during spikes. Aurora Serverless v1 scales in coarser steps with more latency. Pre-warming isn't needed with Serverless v2. Fixed provisioned capacity wastes cost at low traffic."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to implement a multi-region active-passive architecture. The secondary region should only receive traffic if the primary fails. How should they configure Route 53?","options":["A. Use weighted routing with 100% weight on primary and 0% on secondary","B. Use failover routing policy with health checks on the primary endpoint — Route 53 automatically switches to the secondary when the primary fails","C. Use latency routing to prefer the primary region","D. Use geolocation routing to force all traffic to the primary region"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 failover routing designates a primary and secondary record. Health checks monitor the primary. When the primary health check fails, Route 53 automatically returns the secondary record's IP. Weighted routing with 0% never sends traffic to the secondary and doesn't auto-failover. Latency routing might route to a slower secondary region. Geolocation doesn't support failover behavior."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company needs to ensure their Lambda functions continue processing during an AZ failure. Lambda functions are deployed in a VPC. What should the architect verify?","options":["A. Lambda functions automatically span multiple AZs — no VPC configuration needed","B. Ensure the Lambda function's VPC configuration includes subnets in at least 2-3 AZs — Lambda distributes invocations across healthy AZs when one fails","C. Enable Lambda Provisioned Concurrency across all AZs","D. Deploy identical Lambda functions in each AZ separately"],"answer":1,"explain":"When Lambda runs in a VPC, it attaches elastic network interfaces (ENIs) in the specified subnets. Configuring subnets in multiple AZs allows Lambda to use ENIs in healthy AZs if one AZ fails. Without multi-AZ subnets, an AZ failure can cause Lambda invocation failures for VPC-connected functions. Provisioned concurrency is for latency, not AZ resilience. Lambda is a regional service — you don't deploy per-AZ."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company runs an application using API Gateway and Lambda behind CloudFront. During a region-wide event, API Gateway in the primary region becomes unavailable. How can they ensure continuity?","options":["A. CloudFront has a built-in API Gateway failover feature","B. Configure CloudFront with origin failover using an origin group — set the primary origin as the primary region's API Gateway and secondary as a standby region's API Gateway URL","C. Enable API Gateway multi-region deployment — it replicates automatically","D. Use Route 53 to redirect CloudFront to a backup URL"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront origin failover with origin groups allows configuring a primary and secondary origin. If the primary origin returns 5xx errors or is unreachable, CloudFront automatically routes to the secondary origin. This provides transparent failover to a DR region without DNS changes. API Gateway doesn't auto-replicate across regions. Route 53 failover at the DNS level takes minutes due to TTL propagation."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's EventBridge rule triggers a Lambda function that processes order events. Lambda occasionally fails to process orders. They need to ensure no orders are lost and failed orders can be retried. What configuration achieves this?","options":["A. Set the EventBridge rule target retry policy to 0 attempts and handle retries in the Lambda code","B. Configure the EventBridge rule with a retry policy (up to 24 hours / 185 attempts) and a DLQ on the rule target — failed events after all retries go to the DLQ","C. Use CloudWatch alarms to detect Lambda failures and resubmit events manually","D. Enable EventBridge event replay — it automatically retries all events"],"answer":1,"explain":"EventBridge rule targets support retry policies with configurable maximum event age (up to 24 hours) and maximum retry attempts (up to 185). A DLQ on the rule target captures events that exhaust all retries for manual review. Event replay is for replaying events from an archive, not automatic retry of failed targets. CloudWatch alarms are monitoring tools, not retry mechanisms."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company stores configuration data for 1000 EC2 instances in an S3 bucket. Instances read config on startup. The S3 bucket is in us-east-1. They want configuration reads to be available even during an S3 regional issue. What is the best approach?","options":["A. Cache the configuration on instance startup in a local file and reload periodically","B. Enable S3 Cross-Region Replication to a bucket in a second region and configure instances to read from the nearest healthy bucket via Route 53 latency routing","C. Store configuration in EC2 user data — it's highly available","D. Use CloudFront to cache S3 configuration files — CloudFront serves from cache if S3 is unavailable"],"answer":3,"explain":"CloudFront caches S3 content at edge locations. During an S3 regional event, CloudFront can serve cached configuration from the edge, maintaining high availability. TTL should be set appropriately. S3 CRR with Route 53 also works but adds operational complexity. EC2 user data isn't easily updated for 1000 instances. Local caching on instances requires restart or daemon reload."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company's on-premises application is being migrated to AWS. During the migration period, both on-premises and AWS versions must run simultaneously with data kept in sync. What database architecture supports this?","options":["A. Use RDS Multi-AZ with the on-premises instance as the primary","B. Use AWS DMS with continuous replication between on-premises Oracle and AWS RDS, with bi-directional replication if writes occur on both sides","C. Export on-premises data to S3 daily and import to RDS","D. Use AWS DataSync to sync database files between on-premises and AWS"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS DMS with CDC (change data capture) supports ongoing replication during the migration cutover period. For bidirectional sync where both sides receive writes, DMS supports this with careful conflict management. Daily exports have high RPO and don't support real-time synchronization. DataSync handles file and object storage, not database transactions."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company wants to ensure that no single EC2 instance failure affects more than 25% of their application capacity. What is the minimum number of instances needed?","options":["A. 2 instances — 50% impact if one fails","B. 4 instances — if one fails, 75% capacity remains (25% impact)","C. 3 instances — approximately 33% impact if one fails","D. 5 instances — 20% impact if one fails"],"answer":1,"explain":"With 4 instances, losing 1 means 1/4 = 25% capacity loss, which meets the 'no more than 25% impact' requirement exactly. With 3 instances, losing 1 is ~33% impact. With 5, it's 20% (better than required). The minimum to meet the constraint is 4 instances."},{"cat":"resilient-arch","q":"A company uses CloudFront to serve a web application. During a new feature rollout, a bug causes incorrect responses. How can they quickly roll back to the previous working version?","options":["A. Update the CloudFront distribution to point back to the previous origin","B. Use CloudFront continuous deployment policies with traffic weights — set 100% back to the primary distribution immediately","C. Invalidate the CloudFront cache and the origin will serve the old content","D. Use CloudFront Functions to rewrite responses back to the previous format"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront continuous deployment policies allow canary testing with traffic weights between a staging and production distribution. To roll back, set the staging distribution traffic weight to 0 and promote or revert with a single API call. Cache invalidation only removes cached objects — it doesn't change origin behavior. CloudFront Functions add processing but don't roll back origin code."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's web application is experiencing slow database queries. Analysis shows that the same set of product catalog queries are run thousands of times per minute with no data changes. What is the most effective performance improvement?","options":["A. Add an RDS Read Replica and direct all queries to it","B. Implement Amazon ElastiCache for Redis in front of RDS to cache frequent query results","C. Increase the RDS instance size to a larger instance class","D. Partition the RDS database table by product category"],"answer":1,"explain":"ElastiCache for Redis caches query results in memory (sub-millisecond latency) and reduces database load from repeated identical queries. Since product catalog data changes infrequently, a cache TTL of several minutes is appropriate. Read Replicas reduce primary load but still hit the database for every query. Larger instance size helps but doesn't eliminate redundant query processing. Partitioning helps with large datasets but not repetitive read patterns."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A data analytics application processes large datasets on EC2 instances. The team needs the lowest possible network latency between 10 instances running a distributed compute job. What EC2 placement strategy should they use?","options":["A. Spread placement group across multiple racks","B. Cluster placement group — places instances physically close together in a single AZ for high bandwidth (10/25 Gbps) and lowest latency","C. Partition placement group across 3 partitions","D. Deploy instances in the same VPC without any placement group"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cluster placement groups pack instances together within a single AZ, enabling 10-25 Gbps network throughput and ultra-low latency between instances. This is ideal for HPC and tightly coupled distributed compute jobs. Spread groups maximize HA but increase latency. Partition groups isolate large distributed workloads (HDFS, Cassandra). Same VPC without placement groups doesn't guarantee physical proximity."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company serves static and dynamic content from a web application deployed globally. Static content (images, CSS, JS) loads slowly for users in Asia as the servers are in us-east-1. What is the best solution?","options":["A. Deploy EC2 instances in ap-southeast-1 and replicate all content","B. Use Amazon CloudFront to cache and serve static assets from edge locations closest to users globally","C. Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration for the static assets","D. Use Route 53 latency routing to direct Asian users to a separate S3 bucket"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront's global edge network (500+ points of presence) caches static content and delivers it from the nearest location to users. This dramatically reduces latency for global users. EC2 deployment in multiple regions requires content synchronization and is operationally complex. S3 Transfer Acceleration speeds up uploads to S3, not downloads by end users. Latency routing helps with origin selection but doesn't cache content at the edge."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company has an application that queries DynamoDB and frequently reads the same items. They want to reduce DynamoDB latency from single-digit milliseconds to microseconds for hot items. What should they implement?","options":["A. Enable DynamoDB auto-scaling to provision more read capacity","B. Deploy DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) as an in-memory cache — it provides microsecond response times for cached reads","C. Use DynamoDB on-demand mode for unlimited read throughput","D. Add DynamoDB Global Tables to cache reads in multiple regions"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) is a purpose-built in-memory cache for DynamoDB that reduces read latency from milliseconds to microseconds. It's API-compatible with DynamoDB — minimal code changes needed. Auto-scaling adds capacity but DynamoDB is already single-digit milliseconds at scale. On-demand mode scales throughput but doesn't reduce latency. Global Tables provide multi-region replication, not per-region caching."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's application requires a shared file system accessible by 100 EC2 instances simultaneously with POSIX-compliant file access. What storage solution should they use?","options":["A. S3 with the S3 FUSE driver mounted on each instance","B. Amazon EFS (Elastic File System) — provides shared POSIX-compliant NFS access for thousands of concurrent instances","C. EBS Multi-Attach with io2 volumes","D. EC2 instance store with rsync replication between instances"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon EFS provides a fully managed NFS file system with POSIX compliance that can be mounted by thousands of EC2 instances simultaneously across multiple AZs. S3 with FUSE has limitations and performance issues for POSIX workloads. EBS Multi-Attach supports up to 16 instances (Nitro) and requires careful cluster file system management. Instance store with rsync creates consistency issues."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A machine learning training workload requires access to a large dataset stored in S3. Training jobs on multiple EC2 P3 instances are I/O bound, waiting on S3 reads. What improves training throughput?","options":["A. Use S3 Transfer Acceleration for the training data","B. Use Amazon FSx for Lustre integrated with S3 — provides high-performance parallel file system with sub-millisecond latency and hundreds of GB/s throughput, linked to S3","C. Use EFS Provisioned Throughput mode instead of S3","D. Increase EC2 instance count to parallelize S3 reads"],"answer":1,"explain":"FSx for Lustre is a purpose-built high-performance parallel file system designed for ML workloads. It can link to S3 and hydrate data to the Lustre file system for repeated high-speed access. It provides sub-millisecond latency and up to hundreds of GB/s aggregate throughput. S3 Transfer Acceleration speeds up transfers to S3, not reads from S3 by training jobs. EFS doesn't achieve the throughput needed for HPC ML workloads."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's API responds slowly because every request makes multiple sequential database calls. Each call waits for the previous to complete, adding ~100ms per call. What architectural improvement reduces latency?","options":["A. Move the API to Lambda for faster execution","B. Execute independent database queries in parallel using async patterns or concurrent threads, reducing total latency to the slowest single query rather than the sum","C. Increase RDS instance size to handle queries faster","D. Add an API Gateway caching layer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sequential independent queries add latency linearly (N × 100ms). Running independent queries in parallel reduces total latency to max(all queries) instead of sum(all queries). If 5 queries each take 100ms sequentially (500ms total), running in parallel reduces to ~100ms. This is the most impactful change for this specific pattern. Larger RDS improves query speed but doesn't change sequential execution. API Gateway caching helps for repeated identical requests."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's Lambda function loads a 50 MB machine learning model from S3 on every invocation, causing high latency. The model changes once per week. What optimization reduces this?","options":["A. Increase Lambda memory to load the model faster","B. Store the model in /tmp during initialization (outside the handler) so it is reused across warm invocations, or use Lambda Layers for the model file","C. Load the model lazily only when needed","D. Switch to EC2 with the model pre-loaded on an AMI"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda execution environments persist between invocations ('warm' environments). Initializing the model in the global scope (outside the handler function) means it is loaded once and reused across warm invocations. Lambda Layers allow packaging the model as a layer. /tmp storage persists across warm invocations (up to 512MB-10GB depending on configuration). Loading lazily per invocation doesn't improve latency. EC2 is appropriate for always-on inference but loses serverless benefits."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A real-time data pipeline needs to ingest 500,000 events per second from IoT devices, process each event, and store results. Which ingestion service handles this scale?","options":["A. Amazon SQS Standard queue","B. Amazon Kinesis Data Streams with sufficient shards (each shard handles 1,000 records/sec or 1 MB/sec write)","C. Amazon SQS FIFO queue","D. Amazon API Gateway with direct Lambda integration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Data Streams scales horizontally by adding shards. At 500K events/second, the required shard count depends on record size. Kinesis is designed for high-throughput real-time streaming. SQS Standard can handle high throughput but isn't designed for ordered real-time streaming analytics. SQS FIFO is limited to 3,000 msg/sec (with batching) per queue. API Gateway → Lambda would require extreme concurrency and isn't designed for IoT-scale ingestion."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company serves a global web application with content in multiple languages. Pages are generated dynamically based on user location and language. The team wants to reduce origin server load while still personalizing content. What approach achieves this?","options":["A. Cache all pages at CloudFront with a default TTL of 1 day","B. Use CloudFront with cache behaviors based on language/region query strings or cookies, and Lambda@Edge to customize content at the edge before serving from cache","C. Deploy separate EC2 fleets in each AWS region for each language","D. Use Route 53 geolocation routing to direct each user to a region-specific server"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront cache behaviors with query string/cookie forwarding allow caching different versions of pages per language/region combination. Lambda@Edge can perform lightweight personalization at the edge (e.g., redirects, header modification) without hitting the origin. Full per-region EC2 deployments are operationally complex. Route 53 geolocation routing helps but doesn't cache content — still hits the origin per request."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"An application needs to store and query time-series data from 10,000 IoT sensors, generating 100 data points per second per sensor. Queries are time-range based. What is the most appropriate database service?","options":["A. Amazon RDS MySQL with a timestamp index","B. Amazon Timestream — purpose-built for time-series data with automatic tiering, fast time-range queries, and built-in time-series analytics functions","C. Amazon DynamoDB with timestamp sort key","D. Amazon Redshift for all time-series analytics"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Timestream is purpose-built for IoT and operational time-series data. It automatically tiers data between in-memory and magnetic storage, provides built-in time-series functions, and scales to ingest trillions of events per day. RDS MySQL with timestamps works but doesn't scale to 1M data points/second. DynamoDB can store time-series but lacks native time-series analytics. Redshift is for analytical data warehousing, not real-time ingestion."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's Amazon RDS PostgreSQL instance is reaching CPU and IOPS limits during peak hours due to complex analytical queries from a reporting application. What is the most effective solution?","options":["A. Upgrade to a larger RDS instance size","B. Create an RDS Read Replica and direct all reporting queries to the replica, offloading the primary for transactional workloads","C. Enable RDS Multi-AZ to distribute read load between primary and standby","D. Increase RDS storage to SSD (gp3) for better IOPS"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Read Replicas use asynchronous replication to maintain a copy of the database. Directing analytical queries to the replica offloads the primary completely. The RDS Multi-AZ standby is not accessible for read traffic in standard RDS (only in Aurora). Larger instance helps but doesn't address the fundamental issue of mixing OLTP and analytical workloads. SSD storage reduces I/O wait but doesn't reduce CPU usage from complex queries."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to migrate a data warehouse from on-premises to AWS. The warehouse processes petabytes of data with complex SQL queries across many tables. Which AWS service is purpose-built for this?","options":["A. Amazon RDS Aurora PostgreSQL","B. Amazon Redshift with RA3 nodes — columnar storage, massively parallel processing, and Redshift Spectrum for querying S3","C. Amazon EMR with Hive","D. Amazon Athena for all warehouse queries"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Redshift is AWS's managed data warehouse service, purpose-built for complex analytical SQL queries on petabyte-scale data. RA3 nodes separate compute from storage (using Redshift Managed Storage backed by S3). Redshift Spectrum queries data directly in S3. Aurora is an OLTP database. EMR/Hive is for Hadoop-based processing. Athena queries S3 data directly but doesn't provide a persistent warehouse with materialized tables and query optimization."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's application uses Amazon S3 to store millions of small objects. GET request latency is inconsistent and sometimes reaches seconds. What architectural improvement should be made?","options":["A. Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration","B. Use Amazon CloudFront in front of S3 to cache objects at edge locations, ensuring consistent low-latency delivery","C. Move objects to EBS for lower latency","D. Increase S3 request rate by adding a prefix randomization strategy"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront caches S3 objects at edge locations globally, providing consistent low-latency delivery regardless of where users are located. For frequently accessed objects, CloudFront dramatically reduces latency and S3 GET costs. S3 Transfer Acceleration is for faster uploads to S3. EBS is block storage and not suitable for millions of objects. Prefix randomization helps with S3 request rate limits (3,500 PUT/5,500 GET per prefix per second), which was relevant before AWS improved S3 partitioning."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a video streaming application and needs to deliver high-quality video to millions of concurrent viewers globally with adaptive bitrate streaming. What AWS architecture achieves this?","options":["A. Serve video directly from EC2 instances with S3 as storage backend","B. Use Amazon S3 for video storage, AWS Elemental MediaConvert for transcoding to adaptive bitrate (HLS/DASH), and CloudFront for global delivery","C. Use EC2 with GPU instances for video transcoding and delivery","D. Store video in EFS and mount on multiple EC2 instances behind an ALB"],"answer":1,"explain":"This is the standard AWS video-on-demand (VOD) architecture: S3 stores original and transcoded files, MediaConvert converts video to adaptive bitrate formats (HLS/DASH), and CloudFront delivers content from edge locations to millions of concurrent viewers. EC2 for transcoding and delivery requires massive infrastructure management. EFS with EC2 doesn't scale to millions of concurrent viewers and lacks global edge delivery."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company processes large genomics datasets using AWS Batch. Jobs read input data from S3, process it, and write results back to S3. I/O throughput to S3 is the bottleneck. What improves throughput?","options":["A. Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration on the bucket","B. Use S3 multipart upload for large output files, S3 byte-range fetches for parallel reads, and ensure job instances are in the same region as the S3 bucket","C. Move data to EBS io2 volumes for faster access","D. Use S3 Intelligent-Tiering to improve read performance"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 multipart upload parallelizes large file writes. Byte-range GETs parallelize large file reads. Same-region access avoids cross-region data transfer latency and costs. These are standard S3 performance optimization techniques for large-scale data processing. Transfer Acceleration is for cross-internet transfers from outside AWS. EBS io2 isn't appropriate for batch job shared datasets. Intelligent-Tiering manages storage class/cost, not throughput."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's web application has a bottleneck at the database connection pool. The application uses Java with connection pooling and RDS PostgreSQL. During load spikes, the pool exhausts and requests queue or fail. What is the recommended solution?","options":["A. Increase max_connections in RDS PostgreSQL parameter group","B. Deploy Amazon RDS Proxy — it maintains a persistent pool of database connections and multiplexes application connections, handling spikes without exhausting database connections","C. Use PgBouncer on each EC2 application server","D. Add more RDS Read Replicas to distribute connections"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Proxy is a managed proxy that pools and shares database connections. During spikes, hundreds of application requests share a smaller pool of actual database connections. It reduces connection overhead and handles load spikes gracefully. Increasing max_connections has limits based on instance memory. PgBouncer works but requires self-managed deployment on each server. Read Replicas handle read queries, not connection pooling for writes."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Redshift for analytics. Complex queries that join large tables are taking 30+ minutes. What optimization technique should the Solutions Architect recommend first?","options":["A. Add more Redshift compute nodes to increase parallel processing","B. Analyze query execution plans, ensure distribution keys minimize data movement between nodes, and apply sort keys on frequently filtered columns","C. Enable Redshift concurrency scaling","D. Move the queries to Amazon Athena"],"answer":1,"explain":"Optimizing Redshift distribution keys (to co-locate joined data on the same nodes, minimizing data redistribution) and sort keys (to allow zone map pruning on filtered columns) often provides 10-100x query improvement. Adding nodes increases capacity but doesn't fix inefficient distribution. Concurrency scaling adds temporary capacity for concurrent queries but doesn't speed up individual slow queries. Athena doesn't automatically run Redshift queries faster."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs an e-commerce platform where the product search feature is the most performance-critical component. The current MySQL LIKE queries on product names are slow. What is the most performant solution?","options":["A. Add a MySQL full-text search index","B. Use Amazon OpenSearch Service (formerly Elasticsearch) for product search — it provides inverted indexes, relevance scoring, and sub-second search on millions of products","C. Cache the entire product catalog in ElastiCache","D. Use DynamoDB with a GSI on the product name field"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon OpenSearch Service is purpose-built for full-text search with inverted indexes, providing relevance-scored search results in milliseconds across millions of products. MySQL full-text search works but doesn't scale as well or provide the same relevance features. Caching the full catalog in ElastiCache isn't practical for complex search queries. DynamoDB GSIs support exact lookups and prefix queries, not full-text search with relevance scoring."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A financial services company processes stock market data that must be analyzed in real-time as it arrives. Data arrives as a continuous stream and needs to be analyzed within 1 second of arrival. What service is appropriate?","options":["A. Load data into S3 and run Athena queries every minute","B. Use Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics for Apache Flink to process the streaming data with SQL or Java/Scala applications, with sub-second processing latency","C. Load data into Redshift with real-time batch inserts every second","D. Use Lambda functions triggered by SQS to process each record"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Data Analytics for Apache Flink is designed for real-time stream processing with millisecond-to-second latency. It processes data in-flight without storing it first. Flink supports windowed aggregations, joins, and complex event processing. Athena queries S3 data with seconds-to-minutes latency, not real-time. Redshift batch inserts aren't designed for sub-second real-time analytics. SQS → Lambda works but doesn't provide streaming windowed analytics natively."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's application uses EC2 instances backed by EBS gp2 volumes. Storage performance degrades during sustained high I/O workloads as the burst credits are depleted. What is the recommended fix?","options":["A. Increase EBS volume size — gp2 provides 3 IOPS/GB, so larger volume gives more baseline IOPS","B. Migrate to EBS gp3 volumes — gp3 provides a consistent 3,000 IOPS baseline regardless of size, with up to 16,000 IOPS configurable independently of capacity","C. Use EBS io1 volumes for all workloads regardless of cost","D. Enable EBS burst credit monitoring with CloudWatch and add more gp2 volumes"],"answer":1,"explain":"EBS gp3 provides a consistent 3,000 IOPS baseline (not burst-dependent) and allows independently configuring up to 16,000 IOPS and 1,000 MB/s throughput at lower cost than gp2 or io1. gp2 burst credits deplete under sustained I/O, causing exactly the described issue. io1 provides consistent IOPS but at higher cost than needed for most workloads. Multiple gp2 volumes add complexity."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to query log data stored in S3 without loading it into a database. The logs are in JSON format, partitioned by date. They run ad-hoc analytical queries. What is the recommended approach?","options":["A. Use S3 Select to run SQL on individual log files","B. Use Amazon Athena with AWS Glue Data Catalog to query S3 data using standard SQL — partitioning by date enables partition pruning for faster, cheaper queries","C. Load logs into RDS daily for querying","D. Use EMR Hive for all log analytics"],"answer":1,"explain":"Athena queries S3 data in-place using standard SQL without ETL. The Glue Data Catalog defines the schema. Partition pruning on date partitions ensures only relevant data is scanned, reducing cost (charged per TB scanned) and latency. S3 Select works on individual objects, not multi-file analytical queries. RDS loading is costly and slow. EMR Hive works but requires cluster management and is slower for ad-hoc queries than Athena."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's microservices make many small requests to a shared DynamoDB table. The hot partition containing the most popular items is being throttled. What is the most effective resolution?","options":["A. Switch from DynamoDB provisioned to on-demand capacity","B. Review and change the partition key design to distribute writes more evenly — consider adding a random suffix or using a composite key that distributes hot items across partitions","C. Add a DynamoDB Global Secondary Index on the hot items","D. Enable DynamoDB Streams and process hot items separately"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hot partition issues occur when too many requests hit the same partition key. Redesigning the partition key to distribute requests evenly (e.g., adding a hash suffix, using a composite key with higher cardinality) is the most effective long-term fix. On-demand capacity helps with burst but doesn't fix hot partitions — individual partitions still have limits. GSIs replicate data to different partitions but reads on the GSI would still hit the same hot items."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a mobile game with a leaderboard that must display the top 100 players in real-time. The leaderboard updates thousands of times per second. What data store is optimized for this use case?","options":["A. Amazon RDS MySQL with ORDER BY score DESC LIMIT 100","B. Amazon ElastiCache for Redis using a Sorted Set (ZSET) — provides O(log N) score updates and O(log N + k) range queries for real-time leaderboards","C. Amazon DynamoDB with a GSI on score","D. Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL with partitioned tables"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redis Sorted Sets are purpose-built for leaderboard use cases. ZADD updates scores in O(log N), ZREVRANGE retrieves top K players in O(log N + K). This provides sub-millisecond leaderboard operations at any scale. RDS ORDER BY queries scan all records. DynamoDB GSI doesn't support range queries on non-partition-key attributes efficiently for real-time leaderboards. Aurora handles the query but with higher latency than in-memory Redis."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a RESTful API with 50,000 requests per minute. About 80% of requests are for the same top 100 product details, which change hourly. What configuration reduces backend load and improves response time?","options":["A. Deploy more API Gateway stages","B. Enable API Gateway caching with a 1-hour TTL — cache responses for identical requests, serving 80% of traffic from cache without hitting the backend Lambda or EC2","C. Use Lambda reserved concurrency for the product API","D. Add ElastiCache in front of the database only"],"answer":1,"explain":"API Gateway caching with an appropriate TTL caches identical request+response pairs at the API Gateway layer. 80% of requests served from cache means 80% reduction in Lambda invocations and database queries, reducing latency to <10ms for cached responses. Lambda reserved concurrency manages scaling but doesn't reduce invocation count. ElastiCache reduces database load but requests still go through Lambda."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A data processing application on EC2 requires low-latency, high-throughput access to a temporary scratch dataset of 10 TB during processing. Data does not need to persist after the instance terminates. What storage option provides the best performance?","options":["A. EBS gp3 volume attached to the instance","B. EC2 instance store — NVMe SSD directly attached to the physical host, providing the lowest latency and highest I/O throughput with no network overhead","C. Amazon EFS with Max I/O performance mode","D. S3 with multipart download for the scratch dataset"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 instance store (NVMe SSD) is physically attached to the server hosting the EC2 instance, providing the lowest possible latency (no network hop) and highest I/O throughput. For temporary scratch data that doesn't need to persist, instance store is ideal. EBS adds network latency. EFS adds network latency and NFS overhead. S3 is object storage not suitable for low-latency scratch I/O."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company serves user-generated images uploaded to S3. Images are served in multiple sizes (thumbnail, medium, full). Currently, all resizing happens at upload time for all possible sizes. This is slow and wastes storage for sizes that may never be requested. What is a better approach?","options":["A. Pre-generate all sizes using Lambda at upload time — faster than the current approach","B. Generate image sizes on-demand using Lambda@Edge or CloudFront Functions when a specific size is first requested, cache the result in CloudFront — generate only sizes actually needed","C. Store only the original and resize on every request","D. Use Amazon Rekognition to resize images"],"answer":1,"explain":"On-demand image resizing with caching generates only requested sizes, eliminating wasted processing and storage. Lambda@Edge intercepts CloudFront cache misses, resizes the image from the S3 original, and the result is cached at the edge for subsequent requests. Pre-generating all sizes wastes resources. Resizing on every request without caching is the worst performance pattern. Rekognition is for image analysis, not resizing."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Lambda for a high-throughput event processing pipeline. They notice increased latency when Lambda scales from 0 to handling 1,000 concurrent invocations within a few seconds. What is causing this and how do they fix it?","options":["A. Lambda cannot scale to 1,000 concurrent invocations — use EC2 instead","B. Lambda's burst scaling limit causes cold starts when scaling rapidly — use Provisioned Concurrency for predictable traffic patterns and request higher burst limits for sudden spikes","C. Increase Lambda memory allocation to allow faster scaling","D. Use smaller Lambda function packages to reduce cold start time"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda has a burst scaling limit (default 3,000 concurrent invocations added per minute, varies by region). Rapid scaling from 0 to 1,000 causes many cold starts simultaneously. Provisioned Concurrency keeps environments warm for predictable traffic. For unpredictable sudden spikes, request a burst limit increase. Memory increases speed up cold start initialization but don't address burst scaling. Smaller packages reduce cold start time marginally."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's microservices architecture has services communicating via REST APIs. They need a way to discover service endpoints automatically as services scale up and down. What AWS service provides service discovery?","options":["A. Route 53 public hosted zones with manual updates","B. AWS Cloud Map — provides service discovery for cloud resources, integrating with Route 53 and ECS for automatic DNS-based or API-based service registration and discovery","C. Application Load Balancer with path-based routing","D. Amazon API Gateway with Lambda integration"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cloud Map allows services to register themselves with health checks and be discovered by other services via DNS or API calls. It integrates natively with Amazon ECS and EKS for automatic registration. Route 53 public zones expose internal services externally and require manual updates. ALB and API Gateway are traffic management tools, not service discovery mechanisms."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to run database queries that join multiple tables with billions of rows. Query times exceed 10 hours on their current RDS instance. They cannot change the application queries. What architectural change should the Solutions Architect recommend?","options":["A. Upgrade to the largest available RDS instance class","B. Migrate the analytical workload to Amazon Redshift — its columnar storage, massively parallel processing, and query optimization are designed for complex queries on billions of rows","C. Enable RDS Performance Insights and optimize indexes","D. Use RDS Aurora with Parallel Query enabled"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift's columnar storage reads only required columns, MPP distributes query execution across multiple nodes, and query optimization (through distribution keys, sort keys, and query planner) handles complex multi-table joins on billions of rows efficiently — typically in seconds to minutes. RDS is an OLTP database not designed for this scale. Aurora Parallel Query helps but still has OLTP limitations. Index optimization helps for OLTP queries but not for full analytical scans."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company streams real-time events to Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. Multiple consumer applications each need to read the full stream independently at their own pace. What feature should they enable?","options":["A. Configure separate Kinesis shards for each consumer application","B. Enable Kinesis Enhanced Fan-Out — each registered consumer gets a dedicated 2 MB/s per shard throughput pipe, allowing up to 20 consumers to read independently at full speed","C. Create separate Kinesis streams for each consumer","D. Use SQS fan-out via SNS subscription to duplicate messages"],"answer":1,"explain":"Enhanced Fan-Out provides each registered consumer with a dedicated 2 MB/s per shard throughput (using HTTP/2 push model), allowing multiple consumers to read independently without sharing the standard 2 MB/s read limit per shard. Standard shared iterator consumers share the 2 MB/s read limit. Separate shards per consumer doubles the cost. Separate streams duplicate ingestion infrastructure."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's Lambda function processes images and is memory-bound. Doubling memory from 1GB to 2GB reduces execution time from 10 seconds to 4 seconds. Is this cost-effective?","options":["A. No — doubling memory always doubles cost","B. Yes — Lambda pricing is based on GB-seconds (memory × duration). At 1GB: 10 GB-sec. At 2GB: 8 GB-sec. The higher memory option costs less because execution time reduces more than memory increases","C. Memory and cost are unrelated in Lambda","D. Only reduce memory to minimize Lambda costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda charges for GB-seconds (memory × duration in seconds). 1 GB × 10s = 10 GB-sec. 2 GB × 4s = 8 GB-sec. The 2GB option is 20% cheaper AND 60% faster. This counterintuitive result occurs when increasing memory reduces duration more than proportionally. Always benchmark Lambda memory to find the cost-optimal configuration."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to implement a write-heavy workload on DynamoDB (millions of writes per second globally). They have a fixed partition key structure that cannot be changed. What can be done to prevent throttling?","options":["A. Enable DynamoDB auto-scaling with maximum throughput","B. Use DynamoDB write sharding — add a random number suffix (1-N) to the partition key to distribute writes across N logical partitions, then use parallel queries to aggregate reads","C. Use DynamoDB streams to buffer writes","D. Enable DynamoDB on-demand mode to absorb all writes"],"answer":1,"explain":"Write sharding artificially increases partition key cardinality by appending a random suffix. Writes are distributed across N partition key values, spreading load across multiple DynamoDB partitions. On-demand mode can help with sudden bursts but individual hot partitions still have limits. Streams are for change event processing, not write distribution. Auto-scaling responds to throttling after it occurs."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company serves an API from multiple regions. They want requests to be routed to the closest AWS region, with fallback to other regions if one region is unhealthy. Which Route 53 configuration achieves this?","options":["A. Weighted routing with equal weights across all regions","B. Latency-based routing with health checks — routes to the lowest-latency healthy endpoint, automatically failing over to the next best region if the primary is unhealthy","C. Geolocation routing by country to the nearest region","D. Simple routing with lowest TTL possible"],"answer":1,"explain":"Latency-based routing with health checks routes each user to the lowest-latency healthy endpoint. If the closest region's health check fails, Route 53 automatically routes to the next lowest-latency healthy region. Geolocation routing routes based on physical location, not network latency, and doesn't account for route quality. Weighted routing doesn't optimize for latency or handle regional failures."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon SQS for async processing. Message processing takes 2-3 minutes. Consumers are occasionally processing the same message twice. What SQS setting should be adjusted?","options":["A. Increase message retention period","B. Increase the visibility timeout to be longer than the maximum processing time (e.g., 5 minutes) — this prevents the message from becoming visible to other consumers while being processed","C. Enable SQS FIFO queues to prevent duplicate processing","D. Reduce the number of consumer instances"],"answer":1,"explain":"If the visibility timeout is shorter than processing time, SQS makes the message visible again before processing completes, allowing another consumer to pick it up — causing double processing. Setting the visibility timeout longer than the maximum processing time prevents this. FIFO queues provide exactly-once delivery but require API compatibility. Fewer consumers reduce duplicate risk but also reduce throughput."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a multi-tenant SaaS application on AWS. Each tenant's data is stored in a separate DynamoDB table (1000 tenants). Admin dashboards need to query across all tenant tables for operational metrics. This is slow and involves 1000 API calls. What architecture resolves this?","options":["A. Combine all tenant data into a single DynamoDB table with tenant ID as partition key and use Scan for cross-tenant queries","B. Use a single DynamoDB table with tenant ID as partition key — cross-tenant analytics queries use Amazon Athena via DynamoDB export to S3 or DynamoDB Streams to a data lake","C. Use AWS Glue to join all 1000 separate tenant tables","D. Replicate each tenant table to RDS for cross-tenant queries"],"answer":1,"explain":"A single-table design with tenant_id as partition key is the recommended DynamoDB multi-tenancy pattern. For cross-tenant analytics, DynamoDB export to S3 combined with Athena provides efficient cross-tenant queries without individual table API calls. Scanning a shared table for analytics is inefficient. AWS Glue joining 1000 tables is complex. RDS replication of 1000 tables is operationally heavy."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"An application written in Node.js is deployed on AWS Lambda. The function loads a large NPM dependency tree causing 3-second cold starts. What optimization reduces cold start time?","options":["A. Increase Lambda timeout to 30 seconds","B. Use Lambda Layers for shared dependencies, enable Lambda SnapStart (for Java), minimize the deployment package size, and consider bundling with esbuild/webpack to reduce package size","C. Use Node.js 14 instead of Node.js 18","D. Increase Lambda memory to 3GB to speed up initialization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reducing deployment package size is the most effective cold start optimization for Node.js Lambda. Bundling with esbuild/webpack tree-shakes unused code, dramatically reducing package size. Lambda Layers allow dependencies to be cached separately. Note: Lambda SnapStart is currently only for Java — but package optimization and layers apply to Node.js. Increasing timeout doesn't reduce cold start. Node.js version has minimal cold start impact."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs an application on EC2 that handles image processing. Processing a single image requires GPU computation. The workload is bursty — hundreds of images arrive simultaneously then no traffic for hours. What compute option is most suitable?","options":["A. Keep GPU EC2 instances running 24/7 for immediate availability","B. Use Amazon Elastic Inference or deploy GPU EC2 instances (p3/g4dn) via Auto Scaling groups that scale to 0 during idle periods and scale out on queue depth","C. Use Lambda for GPU processing — it supports GPU acceleration","D. Process all images on CPU instances — GPU is not necessary for image processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"GPU EC2 Auto Scaling groups that scale to 0 during idle periods and scale out based on SQS queue depth handle bursty GPU workloads cost-effectively. You only pay for GPU instances when processing jobs. 24/7 GPU instances are expensive for bursty workloads. Lambda does not support GPU. CPU processing is 10-100x slower for deep learning image analysis."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to process 10 TB of log files stored in S3 every night. The processing involves filtering, aggregating, and writing results back to S3. The job must complete within 2 hours. What service is most appropriate?","options":["A. AWS Lambda with SQS trigger — process each log file in a separate Lambda invocation","B. Amazon EMR with Apache Spark — distributes the 10 TB processing across a cluster of EC2 instances, completing in parallel within the time window","C. AWS Glue ETL job with 2 DPUs","D. EC2 single instance with a bash script to process files sequentially"],"answer":1,"explain":"EMR with Spark distributes the processing workload across a cluster. For 10 TB in 2 hours, you size the cluster accordingly (e.g., 10-20 instances). EMR can be configured as transient clusters (spin up for the job, terminate when done). Lambda has 15-minute maximum execution time per invocation — individual large files may exceed this. Glue with only 2 DPUs would be too slow for 10 TB in 2 hours. Single EC2 is not parallelized."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's API is frequently called with the same query parameters by thousands of clients simultaneously during daily batch reporting windows. The backend processes these calls identically. What API optimization reduces redundant processing?","options":["A. Use Lambda Provisioned Concurrency to handle the batch reporting load","B. Implement API Gateway response caching — all clients requesting the same endpoint with the same parameters receive the cached response, processing the backend request only once per TTL period","C. Use SQS to queue all batch reporting API calls","D. Increase Lambda concurrency limits to handle all simultaneous calls"],"answer":1,"explain":"API Gateway caching returns cached responses for identical requests within the TTL window. During batch reporting, all clients requesting the same data receive the cached result while the backend processes the request only once. This dramatically reduces Lambda invocations and backend load. Provisioned Concurrency ensures Lambda is warm but processes every request. SQS makes the API asynchronous. Concurrency limits handle volume but not redundant processing."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's Aurora MySQL cluster is experiencing long-running queries that block other transactions. How can they isolate long-running reporting queries from transactional workloads without separate databases?","options":["A. Schedule long-running queries to run only at night","B. Use Aurora Replicas for read queries — direct OLTP writes and reads to the primary, direct analytical/reporting queries to the Aurora reader endpoint which balances across replicas","C. Increase Aurora instance size to handle both workloads","D. Use Aurora Multi-Master to split writes between nodes"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora Reader endpoints distribute read traffic across Aurora Replicas. Long-running queries on replicas don't block writes on the primary. The primary handles transactional OLTP. Replicas asynchronously receive changes with minimal lag. Scheduling queries at night reduces business hours impact but doesn't separate workloads technically. Aurora Multi-Master (now Aurora limitless) provides multi-writer, not workload isolation. Larger instances don't prevent lock contention."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's on-premises application connects to AWS via Direct Connect. They want to cache AWS service responses on-premises to reduce Direct Connect traffic and latency for frequently accessed data. What AWS service provides this capability?","options":["A. AWS DataSync with local caching agent","B. AWS Storage Gateway (File Gateway) — caches frequently accessed S3 objects on-premises, providing low-latency NFS/SMB access while transparently storing data in S3","C. AWS CloudFront with on-premises points of presence","D. Route 53 Resolver with response caching"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Storage Gateway File Gateway caches the most recently used data on-premises, providing low-latency access for hot data while storing the full dataset in S3. This reduces Direct Connect bandwidth for repeated access to the same files. DataSync is for data migration and synchronization, not caching. CloudFront edge locations are in AWS regions and major internet hubs, not customer on-premises locations. Route 53 Resolver caches DNS, not application data."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon CloudFront. When the origin server returns a 503 error, CloudFront serves a stale cached response instead of showing users an error. How can they configure this behavior?","options":["A. Enable CloudFront Origin Shield","B. Configure CloudFront Cache-Control headers with stale-while-revalidate directive and enable origin failover","C. Enable CloudFront stale-if-error with a TTL — serve the last cached response when the origin returns 5xx errors up to the configured time","D. Use Lambda@Edge to catch 5xx errors and serve a custom response"],"answer":2,"explain":"CloudFront stale-if-error allows serving cached content when the origin returns 5xx errors for a configurable duration. This maintains user experience during origin outages by serving potentially stale but functional content. Origin failover routes to a secondary origin on 5xx errors. Origin Shield adds a caching layer in front of the origin but doesn't serve stale content on failure. Lambda@Edge can handle errors but adds latency and cost."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to migrate 50 TB of data from on-premises to Amazon S3 over a slow 1 Gbps WAN link that would take weeks via the internet. They need the data transferred in 3 days. What AWS service achieves this?","options":["A. Use S3 Transfer Acceleration over the existing WAN link","B. Use AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized — an 80 TB physical device shipped to the data center, data is loaded offline and shipped to AWS, bypassing network limitations","C. Use AWS Direct Connect at 10 Gbps","D. Use parallel multipart uploads with multiple S3 endpoints"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Snowball Edge allows offline data transfer. A 50TB dataset can be loaded in 1-2 days using Snowball's local storage and then shipped to AWS. AWS loads data into S3 after receipt, meeting the 3-day window without network constraints. S3 Transfer Acceleration and multipart uploads optimize internet transfers but 50 TB over 1 Gbps still takes several days minimum. Setting up a new 10 Gbps Direct Connect connection takes weeks."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a social media application where each user can follow thousands of other users. Loading a user's feed requires aggregating posts from all followed users. This query is very slow. What data architecture improvement helps?","options":["A. Use RDS with complex JOIN queries and increase instance size","B. Pre-compute and materialize the feed using a fan-out write strategy — when a user posts, write the post to the feeds of all followers in DynamoDB or ElastiCache, making feed reads O(1) instead of O(followers)","C. Use Amazon Neptune for social graph queries","D. Cache the full user post history in ElastiCache per user"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fan-out on write pre-computes feeds at write time. When User A posts, their post is immediately added to the feed tables/caches of all N followers. Feed reads become a simple lookup instead of aggregating across all followed users. This trades write overhead for dramatically faster reads — correct for read-heavy social media. Neptune handles graph traversal (finding followers) but doesn't pre-compute feeds."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company stores time-series sensor data in Amazon S3 in JSON format. Queries using Athena are slow and expensive because they scan all data even for recent queries. What partitioning strategy improves this?","options":["A. Use Athena CTAS to convert all data to ORC format","B. Partition data in S3 by year/month/day and use Athena partition projection — queries with date filters scan only relevant partitions, dramatically reducing data scanned and query cost","C. Enable Athena query result caching for all queries","D. Use S3 Select instead of Athena for all queries"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 partitioning by date (s3://bucket/year=2024/month=03/day=15/) combined with Athena partition projection allows Athena to prune irrelevant partitions based on WHERE clause date filters. Queries on recent data scan only recent partitions, not the entire dataset. ORC format improves column pruning but doesn't address partition scanning. Athena result caching helps for repeated identical queries. S3 Select queries individual objects, not analytical multi-file datasets."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's application makes 1,000 read API calls per second to a third-party API that has a rate limit of 100 calls per second. Requests are failing due to rate limiting. What AWS architecture pattern resolves this?","options":["A. Increase Lambda concurrency to make calls faster","B. Implement an SQS queue to buffer outgoing API calls and a Lambda consumer that respects the rate limit (100/sec) with retry logic and exponential backoff on rate limit errors","C. Use CloudFront to cache third-party API responses","D. Switch to a CDN-backed version of the third-party API"],"answer":1,"explain":"SQS as a buffer decouples the internal request rate (1,000/sec) from the outbound API call rate (100/sec). Lambda reads from SQS at the permitted rate of 100 calls/second. Failed calls due to rate limiting are retried. CloudFront can cache third-party API responses if they're cacheable, but not all API responses are idempotent or cacheable. Lambda concurrency increases the problem by calling faster."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company wants to improve read performance for their Amazon Aurora cluster. They have 5 Aurora Replicas across 2 AZs. The application currently connects to the cluster reader endpoint. They want individual consumers to get dedicated throughput. What Aurora feature should they use?","options":["A. Create 5 separate Aurora clusters, one per consumer","B. Create custom Aurora endpoints for specific replica subsets — assign different replica subsets to different consumer groups so each gets dedicated reader throughput","C. Use Aurora Auto Scaling to add more replicas dynamically","D. Migrate to DynamoDB for better read scalability"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora custom endpoints allow creating named endpoints that route to a specific subset of replicas. You can create a custom endpoint for reporting (pointing to 2 high-memory replicas) and another for application reads (pointing to 3 other replicas). This gives dedicated throughput to each consumer group. Separate clusters add management overhead and storage costs. Auto scaling adds capacity but doesn't provide isolation between consumers."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company receives large CSV files (50-500 MB each) into an S3 bucket. A Lambda function processes each file but is hitting the 15-minute execution time limit. What architecture resolves this?","options":["A. Increase Lambda memory to process files faster","B. Use S3 event notifications to trigger an AWS Batch job or an EMR step for large files, or split files on upload using S3 Object Lambda to process in chunks","C. Move the Lambda to a container and increase the timeout","D. Use Step Functions to chain multiple Lambda functions processing the file sequentially"],"answer":1,"explain":"Large file processing exceeding Lambda's 15-minute limit should use AWS Batch (for containerized jobs with no time limit) or EMR. Alternatively, splitting files into chunks allows Lambda to process each chunk within the time limit. Step Functions chaining Lambda functions can workaround the limit but complicates logic. Container Lambda has the same 15-minute limit. More memory speeds processing but doesn't address the 15-minute hard limit."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company wants to store and serve 100 million small JSON documents (average 1 KB). The primary access pattern is fetching a document by a unique ID. Which storage option provides the lowest latency at scale?","options":["A. Amazon RDS MySQL with an indexed id column","B. Amazon DynamoDB with the document ID as the partition key — single-digit millisecond read latency at any scale","C. Amazon S3 with documents organized by ID in the key name","D. Amazon EFS with documents stored as files"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB is designed for high-throughput, low-latency key-based access to any volume of data. GetItem by partition key provides single-digit millisecond latency. RDS adds query planning overhead. S3 GetObject has 10-50ms typical latency and is optimized for large objects. EFS NFS protocol adds overhead for millions of small files."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's web application uses an ALB and an Auto Scaling group. During Black Friday, the Auto Scaling group takes 8 minutes to launch new instances due to AMI boot time. What reduces instance launch time?","options":["A. Use smaller instance types that boot faster","B. Use pre-built golden AMIs that include all application code and dependencies pre-installed, avoiding bootstrap scripts that install software at launch time","C. Increase the Auto Scaling cooldown period","D. Use Spot Instances which launch faster than On-Demand"],"answer":1,"explain":"Golden AMIs with pre-installed software eliminate the time spent running bootstrap scripts (installing dependencies, pulling code from repos) during instance launch. Boot time goes from 8 minutes to typically under 2 minutes. Smaller instances boot at similar speed. Cooldown periods slow scaling. Spot Instances have the same boot process."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses AWS CloudFront. Their dynamic API responses (unique per user) are being accidentally cached and served to other users. What configuration prevents this?","options":["A. Disable CloudFront entirely for the API","B. Configure CloudFront cache behavior for the API paths with Cache-Control: no-cache or min-TTL=0, and forward all request headers and cookies used to differentiate user responses","C. Use a separate CloudFront distribution for static and dynamic content","D. Enable CloudFront signed URLs for all API requests"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dynamic user-specific content should not be cached. Setting TTL to 0 or Cache-Control: no-cache ensures CloudFront always fetches from the origin for these requests. Forwarding differentiating headers/cookies creates separate cache entries per user, preventing cross-user contamination even if some caching is desired. Signed URLs control access but don't prevent caching. Separate distributions help organization but don't prevent caching."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"An application uses Amazon RDS MySQL and the performance team observes high IOPS with many small random reads. The data access pattern shows repeated access to a small subset of records. What is the most targeted optimization?","options":["A. Increase RDS IOPS allocation","B. Enable RDS caching using Amazon ElastiCache — cache the hot small subset of records in memory to eliminate repeated disk I/O","C. Add read replicas to distribute the IOPS","D. Use Aurora instead of RDS MySQL for better IOPS"],"answer":1,"explain":"When a small subset of records is accessed repeatedly, in-memory caching with ElastiCache eliminates the disk I/O entirely for those hot records. This is more cost-effective than increasing IOPS allocation or adding replicas that still hit disk. Aurora provides better IOPS than RDS MySQL but the core issue (repeated disk reads for hot data) is better solved with application-level caching."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to deliver streaming data to S3. Data arrives in small batches. Athena queries on the S3 data are slow because millions of small files are created. What Firehose configuration improves Athena query performance?","options":["A. Increase Kinesis Data Streams shard count","B. Configure Kinesis Data Firehose with dynamic partitioning and set the buffer size to 128 MB and buffer interval to 300 seconds — larger buffers create fewer, larger files that Athena queries more efficiently","C. Use Kinesis Data Analytics instead of Firehose","D. Enable S3 Intelligent-Tiering on the destination bucket"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis Firehose buffers records before writing to S3. Larger buffer size (up to 128MB) and longer buffer interval (up to 900 seconds) combine records into larger files. Athena performs better with fewer large files than many small files due to S3 API call overhead and file-per-task overhead in query execution. Dynamic partitioning routes data to appropriate S3 prefixes. Shard count affects Kinesis Streams, not Firehose."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's application on EC2 needs to download the same 10 GB reference dataset from S3 every time a new instance launches. This adds 15 minutes to startup time. What is the most effective optimization?","options":["A. Use S3 Transfer Acceleration to speed up the download","B. Pre-bake the dataset into the AMI or use EC2 launch template user data to download from a cached EBS snapshot, or cache in a shared EFS mount that new instances can access immediately","C. Use EC2 instance store for the dataset — it transfers faster","D. Increase EC2 network bandwidth by using an enhanced networking instance type"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-baking data into an AMI eliminates download time entirely. Alternatively, an EBS snapshot pre-loaded with the data can be attached quickly. A shared EFS mount allows immediate read access to the dataset. S3 Transfer Acceleration and enhanced networking reduce download time but don't eliminate the 15-minute wait. Instance store cannot be pre-populated from an external source during launch."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a multiplayer game server on EC2. Players experience high latency when connecting from different continents. The game requires TCP connections. What AWS service improves connection latency for global players?","options":["A. CloudFront — it supports TCP game traffic","B. AWS Global Accelerator — routes TCP/UDP traffic through AWS's global network backbone to the optimal AWS region edge, reducing latency by 60% for global users","C. Route 53 latency routing to the nearest region","D. Direct Connect from all player locations"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Global Accelerator uses the AWS global network backbone instead of the public internet, providing consistent low-latency routing to the nearest AWS edge location, then high-speed routing to the game servers. It supports TCP and UDP (unlike CloudFront which is HTTP/S). Route 53 latency routing directs DNS resolution but doesn't route traffic over the AWS backbone. Direct Connect is for enterprise on-premises connections, not consumer game players."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon SQS. Consumers process messages in 1 second. The team wants maximum throughput for the consumer fleet. What SQS configuration maximizes throughput?","options":["A. Use long polling with ReceiveMessage WaitTimeSeconds set to 0 (short polling)","B. Use long polling (WaitTimeSeconds=20) with ReceiveMessage MaxNumberOfMessages=10 — this retrieves up to 10 messages per API call efficiently and reduces empty responses","C. Create many small SQS queues and use fan-out","D. Use SQS FIFO for better throughput"],"answer":1,"explain":"Long polling reduces empty responses (when the queue is empty, it waits up to 20 seconds for a message instead of returning immediately). Requesting up to 10 messages per API call reduces API call overhead and maximizes per-call throughput. Short polling wastes API calls on empty responses. FIFO queues have lower maximum throughput than Standard queues. Multiple queues add consumer complexity."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company stores 1 petabyte of log data in Amazon S3 in Apache Parquet format partitioned by date. They want to enable data analysts to run ad-hoc SQL queries with response times under 10 seconds for typical queries. What should the architect recommend?","options":["A. Load all data into RDS Aurora for SQL access","B. Use Amazon Athena with AWS Glue Data Catalog — Parquet columnar format with date partitioning enables fast, cost-efficient queries with Athena's serverless MPP engine","C. Use Amazon Redshift with COPY command to load all 1 PB","D. Deploy an Apache Spark cluster on EMR for ad-hoc queries"],"answer":1,"explain":"Athena with Parquet + date partitions is ideal for ad-hoc queries on petabyte-scale S3 data. Parquet's columnar format allows column pruning. Date partitions allow partition pruning. Athena's serverless MPP executes queries in seconds without cluster management. Loading 1 PB into Redshift takes significant time and cost. EMR Spark handles complex queries but requires cluster provisioning. Aurora isn't designed for petabyte-scale analytical workloads."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's Lambda functions write logs to CloudWatch Logs. As the application scales, logging becomes expensive. Detailed DEBUG logs are needed only during incidents. How should they optimize logging costs?","options":["A. Disable all logging from Lambda functions","B. Implement structured logging with log levels — emit INFO/ERROR in production, enable DEBUG via Lambda environment variable changes only during troubleshooting, and use CloudWatch log retention policies to expire old logs","C. Log all output to S3 instead of CloudWatch","D. Use X-Ray instead of CloudWatch for all application logging"],"answer":1,"explain":"Structured logging with configurable log levels reduces log volume dramatically. Environment variables control log level without code changes. Retention policies automatically expire old logs, reducing storage cost. Disabling all logging removes operational visibility. S3 logging adds application complexity and doesn't integrate with CloudWatch monitoring. X-Ray is for distributed tracing, not general-purpose logging."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company serves an API used by mobile apps. 95% of requests are for data that changes less than once per minute. API Gateway + Lambda + DynamoDB latency is 150ms average. They want to reduce this to under 20ms for the majority of requests. What is the most effective optimization?","options":["A. Use Lambda Provisioned Concurrency","B. Implement caching at the API Gateway level (Stage cache) or use CloudFront in front of API Gateway with a short TTL — serve cached responses in <10ms for the 95% of requests to unchanging data","C. Switch from Lambda to EC2 for the API backend","D. Enable DynamoDB DAX to reduce database latency"],"answer":1,"explain":"API Gateway caching or CloudFront caching serves cached responses in <10ms without invoking Lambda or querying DynamoDB. For data that changes less than once per minute, a 60-second TTL serves 95% of requests from cache. This provides 150ms → <10ms improvement for cached responses. Provisioned Concurrency reduces cold starts but still invokes Lambda (100+ ms). DAX reduces DynamoDB latency but still involves Lambda execution."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's application reads a configuration file from S3 on every Lambda invocation (100,000 invocations/hour). The config changes at most once per day. This adds 50ms latency per invocation. What optimization should they implement?","options":["A. Use S3 Transfer Acceleration for faster config reads","B. Load the configuration file once in the Lambda initialization phase (outside the handler) and cache it in a module-level variable — subsequent warm invocations reuse the cached config without S3 reads","C. Store the config in Lambda environment variables (up to 4 KB)","D. Use AWS AppConfig for configuration management"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda's execution environment persists between warm invocations. Initializing the config in the global scope means the S3 read happens only once per execution environment (typically lasting hours). The handler reuses the cached config on warm invocations. For configs ≤4KB, environment variables work but require Lambda redeployment to update. AppConfig is the enterprise solution with hot-swapping but adds complexity. S3 Transfer Acceleration speeds downloads but doesn't eliminate them."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company runs a high-traffic website with a CDN. During a flash sale, the CDN has a low cache hit ratio because each product URL includes a unique session identifier in the query string. What should they fix?","options":["A. Disable query string forwarding entirely in CloudFront","B. Configure CloudFront to not cache the session-specific query string parameter (use cache policy that ignores session_id) while still caching other query strings — cache key contains only relevant parameters","C. Increase CloudFront cache TTL to 24 hours","D. Use Lambda@Edge to strip session IDs before caching"],"answer":1,"explain":"The session ID in the query string creates a unique cache key per user, causing every request to miss the cache. Configuring CloudFront's cache policy to exclude the session_id query parameter from the cache key allows identical product page content to be cached and served to all users regardless of their session ID. The session_id can still be forwarded to the origin separately if needed."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A data engineering team needs to run complex ETL jobs that join datasets from S3, RDS, and DynamoDB. Jobs should run on a schedule without managing servers. What AWS service is most appropriate?","options":["A. AWS Lambda with custom ETL code","B. AWS Glue — serverless ETL service that auto-generates PySpark scripts, has built-in connectors for S3/RDS/DynamoDB, and runs on managed Spark infrastructure with automatic scaling","C. Amazon EMR with permanent cluster","D. AWS Data Pipeline"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Glue is a serverless ETL service that handles the ETL heavy lifting: schema discovery (Crawlers), code generation (PySpark), and execution on managed Spark infrastructure. It natively connects to S3, RDS, DynamoDB, and other sources. Lambda's 15-minute timeout is insufficient for complex ETL. EMR requires cluster management. AWS Data Pipeline is older and less feature-rich than Glue for modern ETL."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company's API Gateway is processing 1 million requests/day. 30% of these are failed requests (4xx/5xx errors) from bots and scrapers. This wastes Lambda execution costs. What reduces these wasteful invocations?","options":["A. Enable API Gateway throttling with usage plans and API keys","B. Configure AWS WAF with bot control managed rules in front of API Gateway — block known bot traffic before it reaches the API, eliminating Lambda invocations for bot requests","C. Add request validation in Lambda to reject bad requests early","D. Deploy API Gateway with VPC link to prevent external access"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS WAF with Bot Control managed rules identifies and blocks known bot traffic at the API Gateway perimeter, before Lambda is invoked. This eliminates Lambda costs for the 30% bot traffic. Request validation in Lambda still invokes (and charges for) Lambda before rejecting. API key throttling controls legitimate traffic patterns. VPC link restricts to VPC traffic, blocking legitimate external users."},{"cat":"high-perf-arch","q":"A company needs to synchronize files between on-premises storage and Amazon S3 on a scheduled basis. Files can be hundreds of gigabytes. They need efficient incremental sync (only changed files). What service is designed for this?","options":["A. AWS S3 CLI with aws s3 sync run via cron","B. AWS DataSync — purpose-built for high-speed data transfer with automatic incremental detection (file modification time and checksum), parallel transfer, and network optimization","C. AWS Database Migration Service (DMS)","D. AWS Snowball Edge for each scheduled sync"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS DataSync handles scheduled data transfers with automatic change detection (modification time, checksum), parallel multi-threaded transfer, bandwidth throttling, and task scheduling. It's significantly faster than S3 CLI sync due to parallel multi-connection transfers. DMS is for database migrations. Snowball is for one-time large offline transfers, not recurring scheduled syncs."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company has a stable, predictable workload running on 20 EC2 On-Demand instances 24/7. They have been running this workload for 2 years and plan to continue for 3 more years. What is the most cost-effective pricing option?","options":["A. Continue with On-Demand pricing","B. Purchase 3-year Reserved Instances (All Upfront) — provides up to 72% discount over On-Demand for predictable, steady-state workloads","C. Use Spot Instances for 90% savings","D. Purchase Savings Plans with a 1-year commitment"],"answer":1,"explain":"3-year All Upfront Reserved Instances provide the maximum discount (up to 72%) for predictable, long-running workloads. For a 5-year total run, 3-year RIs are appropriate. Spot Instances can be interrupted — unsuitable for mission-critical steady-state workloads. 1-year Savings Plans provide ~40-60% savings, less than 3-year RIs. On-Demand is the most expensive option for predictable workloads."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs a batch analytics job every night for 4 hours using 10 large EC2 instances. The job is fault-tolerant and can be restarted. What is the most cost-effective compute option?","options":["A. On-Demand Instances — guaranteed availability for the nightly job","B. Reserved Instances — 24/7 discount even for nightly use","C. Spot Instances — up to 90% savings, and since the job is fault-tolerant and can restart, interruptions are acceptable","D. Savings Plans — provide discounts for all EC2 usage"],"answer":2,"explain":"Spot Instances offer up to 90% discount over On-Demand. For fault-tolerant batch jobs that run 4 hours with checkpointing, Spot interruptions are acceptable — the job can resume from a checkpoint. On-Demand guarantees availability but is the most expensive. Reserved Instances commit to 24/7 payment even when the job only runs 4 hours/day. Savings Plans provide discounts but less than Spot for interruptible workloads."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores 500 TB of data in S3 Standard. Analysis shows 90% of the data hasn't been accessed in over 90 days. What is the most cost-effective S3 change?","options":["A. Delete the data older than 90 days to save storage costs","B. Implement S3 Lifecycle policies to automatically transition objects to S3 Standard-IA after 30 days and S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval after 90 days, reducing storage costs by up to 80%","C. Enable S3 Intelligent-Tiering on all objects","D. Move all data to a single S3 Glacier archive immediately"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Lifecycle policies automate the transition to cheaper storage classes based on age. Standard-IA costs ~58% less than Standard with retrieval fees. Glacier costs ~83% less. For 90% inactive data, lifecycle policies dramatically reduce costs. S3 Intelligent-Tiering is ideal for unpredictable access patterns but has monitoring fees per object. Immediate Glacier migration means slow retrieval for the 10% that might be accessed. Deleting data may violate retention requirements."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs 200 EC2 instances across various services with a mix of instance types and regions. They want to reduce costs without changing architecture. What should the Solutions Architect review first?","options":["A. Switch all instances to the smallest available instance type","B. Use AWS Cost Explorer's rightsizing recommendations and AWS Trusted Advisor to identify underutilized instances and purchase Reserved Instances or Savings Plans for consistently used resources","C. Terminate all unused development instances","D. Enable detailed billing and review next month"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cost Explorer rightsizing and Trusted Advisor identify specific underutilized instances with data-driven recommendations. Purchasing Savings Plans or RIs for consistently running instances provides immediate savings. Rightsizing followed by commitment purchasing is the standard AWS cost optimization approach. Blindly downsizing all instances may impact performance. Terminating dev instances helps but requires identifying which are truly unused first."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon S3 to store application logs. The logs must be retained for 7 years for compliance, but are only actively analyzed in the first 30 days. After 1 year, they are rarely retrieved. What lifecycle policy minimizes cost?","options":["A. Store all logs in S3 Standard for 7 years","B. Transition logs to S3 Standard-IA after 30 days, to S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval after 90 days, to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 1 year — Deep Archive is the lowest-cost long-term storage","C. Compress logs with Lambda and store in a single S3 object","D. Use S3 Intelligent-Tiering for all 7 years — it auto-optimizes storage class"],"answer":1,"explain":"This lifecycle policy matches storage class to access frequency: Standard for hot access (0-30 days), Standard-IA for occasional access (30-90 days), Glacier Instant for rare access (90 days-1 year), Glacier Deep Archive for archival (1-7 years). Deep Archive ($0.00099/GB/month) is 95% cheaper than Standard. Intelligent-Tiering doesn't tier to Deep Archive automatically and has per-object monitoring fees that may exceed savings for small objects."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A startup runs a development/test environment with EC2 instances that are only used 8 hours per day during business hours (Monday–Friday). What is the most cost-effective way to manage these instances?","options":["A. Purchase Reserved Instances for the dev environment","B. Use AWS Instance Scheduler or Lambda + EventBridge to automatically stop instances after hours and on weekends — reduces running hours by ~75%","C. Use Spot Instances for dev/test workloads","D. Reduce instance sizes to minimize cost"],"answer":1,"explain":"Stopping instances when not in use (8 hours/day × 5 days = 40 hours/week vs 168 hours) reduces running costs by ~76%. EC2 charges only for running hours. Instance Scheduler automates start/stop. For dev/test, this is the highest-impact change. Spot Instances also work well for dev/test (and can be combined with scheduling). RIs for dev environments are wasteful — you pay 24/7 for instances only used 24% of the time."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company's data warehouse queries run complex analytics on historical data in Amazon Redshift. Cluster utilization is under 20% most of the time but spikes to 80% for 2 hours each morning when reports run. What is the most cost-optimized architecture?","options":["A. Right-size the cluster to handle peak load 24/7","B. Use Redshift concurrency scaling (additional clusters auto-added during peak) and consider Redshift Serverless for variable workloads — pay only for compute used during queries","C. Use a fixed large cluster 24/7 and accept the idle cost","D. Schedule all queries to run at the same time to maximize cluster utilization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redshift concurrency scaling automatically adds cluster capacity during peak demand and charges only for the additional burst capacity. Redshift Serverless charges per RPU-hour during query execution, ideal for variable workloads with long idle periods. A fixed large cluster pays 24/7 for 80% peak but runs at 20% most of the time. Bunching all queries removes scheduling flexibility."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs a large-scale web application with highly variable traffic (10x spikes during events). The application is containerized on ECS Fargate. How can they minimize costs while handling spikes?","options":["A. Provision Fargate capacity for peak load at all times","B. Use Fargate Spot for tasks that can tolerate interruption (background/batch tasks) and On-Demand Fargate for the web frontend — set up auto scaling to match demand","C. Move the entire application to EC2 Reserved Instances","D. Pre-purchase Fargate capacity reservations"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fargate Spot provides up to 70% savings for interruption-tolerant workloads. On-Demand Fargate for user-facing services ensures availability. Fargate auto scaling adjusts task count with demand, so you only pay for what you use during low traffic. Pre-provisioning for peak wastes cost during normal traffic. EC2 Reserved Instances require predicting capacity and managing instances."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company migrated to AWS and their data transfer costs are higher than expected. Analysis shows EC2 instances in us-east-1 are transferring large amounts of data to EC2 instances in eu-west-1. What architecture change reduces this cost?","options":["A. Use VPC peering instead of the public internet for inter-region traffic","B. Redesign the application to minimize cross-region data transfer — colocate services that exchange large amounts of data in the same region or use regional deployments with eventual synchronization","C. Use Direct Connect for all inter-region traffic","D. Enable VPC Flow Logs to understand traffic patterns before making changes"],"answer":1,"explain":"The most effective cost reduction is architectural: minimize the amount of data that crosses regions. Colocating tightly coupled services in the same region eliminates inter-region transfer costs. VPC peering and Direct Connect reduce transfer per-GB cost slightly for approved traffic but don't eliminate the volume. Flow Logs provide visibility (useful first step) but VPC peering doesn't change the fundamental cost model for inter-region traffic."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is using Amazon RDS MySQL with a db.r5.8xlarge instance (64 vCPUs, 256 GB RAM). CloudWatch metrics show average CPU at 8% and memory at 30%. What is the recommended action?","options":["A. Keep the current instance size for future growth","B. Downsize the RDS instance — use AWS Compute Optimizer or RDS Performance Insights to identify the optimal instance size based on actual usage patterns, potentially saving 60-80% on the RDS cost","C. Enable RDS Multi-AZ — it distributes the load and reduces per-instance cost","D. Add read replicas to handle the excess capacity"],"answer":1,"explain":"An instance at 8% CPU and 30% memory is significantly over-provisioned. Downsizing to a db.r5.xlarge or db.r5.2xlarge based on actual workload saves 60-80% on RDS costs. AWS Compute Optimizer and RDS recommendations provide specific sizing guidance. Multi-AZ doubles the cost. Read replicas add cost, not reduce it. Future growth justification should be based on growth projections, not raw fear of running out."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company wants to reduce their Amazon CloudWatch costs. They have 500 EC2 instances with detailed monitoring (1-minute metrics) enabled. Most instances are stable and don't require 1-minute granularity. What should they do?","options":["A. Disable all CloudWatch monitoring to save costs","B. Switch stable instances from detailed monitoring (1-minute) to basic monitoring (5-minute) — basic monitoring is free for EC2 instances, while detailed monitoring charges per metric","C. Export CloudWatch metrics to S3 and delete them from CloudWatch","D. Use AWS X-Ray instead of CloudWatch metrics"],"answer":1,"explain":"EC2 basic monitoring (5-minute intervals) is free and included in EC2 pricing. Detailed monitoring (1-minute intervals) costs $0.30 per instance per month. With 500 instances, switching stable ones to basic monitoring saves hundreds of dollars monthly. Disabling monitoring removes operational visibility. S3 export doesn't reduce CloudWatch charges. X-Ray is for application tracing, not infrastructure metrics."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs a serverless application with Lambda and DynamoDB. Lambda costs are higher than expected. AWS Cost Explorer shows high GB-seconds usage. What should they analyze first?","options":["A. Reduce the number of Lambda functions","B. Analyze Lambda memory allocation vs actual memory used (AWS Lambda Power Tuning or CloudWatch memory metrics) — right-size each function to the minimum memory that meets performance requirements","C. Switch all Lambda functions to ARM (Graviton2) architecture — 20% cheaper and often faster","D. Increase Lambda function timeout to allow more processing per invocation"],"answer":2,"explain":"Lambda Graviton2 (ARM) architecture provides up to 20% better price-performance than x86 for most workloads with a simple architecture flag change. Combined with right-sizing memory (overprovisioned Lambda memory directly increases GB-seconds cost), these two changes typically reduce Lambda costs significantly. Reducing function count changes architecture. Increasing timeout increases GB-seconds cost. Right-sizing is important but Graviton2 is a quick win with minimal effort."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores large video files in Amazon S3 Standard. After 90 days, videos are rarely accessed but must be retrieved within 12 hours when needed. What S3 storage class is most cost-effective for this requirement?","options":["A. S3 Standard-IA — lower cost than Standard with millisecond retrieval","B. S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval — up to 90% cheaper than Standard with retrieval times of 1 minute to 12 hours depending on retrieval type selected","C. S3 Glacier Deep Archive — lowest cost but 12-48 hour retrieval","D. S3 One Zone-IA — cheapest option for infrequent access"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval (formerly S3 Glacier) costs ~83% less than Standard and supports Bulk retrieval in 5-12 hours and Standard retrieval in 3-5 hours — both meeting the 12-hour requirement. Glacier Deep Archive's minimum retrieval time is 12 hours (Bulk) which barely meets the requirement but Standard retrieval is 48 hours. Standard-IA is more expensive than Glacier and appropriate for 1-4x per month access. One Zone-IA loses an AZ but still costs more than Glacier."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses multiple AWS accounts under AWS Organizations. They purchase Reserved Instances in the master payer account. Which accounts benefit from the RI discounts?","options":["A. Only the account where the RI was purchased","B. RI discounts apply across all accounts in the organization by default (RI sharing is enabled) — any account in the organization using matching EC2 instances receives the discounted rate","C. Only accounts in the same OU as the purchasing account","D. Discounts must be manually transferred to member accounts"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Organizations enables RI sharing by default. Reserved Instance and Savings Plans discounts automatically apply to matching usage across all member accounts in the organization. This allows central purchasing in a master account to benefit all member accounts. RI sharing can be disabled per account if needed. There is no manual transfer process — it's automatic."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is deciding between Amazon Aurora Serverless v2 and provisioned Aurora for a new application with unpredictable usage (idle most of the day with random spikes). What is the cost consideration?","options":["A. Provisioned Aurora always costs less than Serverless","B. Aurora Serverless v2 is more cost-effective for variable workloads — it scales to 0.5 ACU minimum when idle (vs. provisioned instances that charge even when idle), while scaling instantly to handle spikes","C. Aurora Serverless v2 and provisioned Aurora cost the same per hour","D. Aurora Serverless v1 is cheaper than Serverless v2 for all use cases"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora Serverless v2 bills per ACU-hour and scales down to 0.5 ACU minimum during idle periods, significantly reducing idle costs compared to provisioned instances (which charge the full instance hourly rate). For applications idle most of the day, Serverless v2 can be 60-80% cheaper. Serverless v1 scaled in coarser increments and had higher minimum capacity. Provisioned instances are more cost-effective for predictable high-utilization workloads."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company wants to optimize their AWS data transfer costs. They have EC2 instances downloading data from an S3 bucket in the same region. What is the cost impact?","options":["A. S3 to EC2 data transfer in the same region costs the standard data transfer rate","B. Data transfer from S3 to EC2 instances in the same AWS region is free — there is no data transfer charge for intra-region S3 to EC2 transfers","C. Data transfer between S3 and EC2 costs $0.01/GB in the same region","D. All S3 data egress is charged at $0.09/GB regardless of destination"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS does not charge for data transfer between Amazon S3 and Amazon EC2 instances within the same region. This is a key cost optimization — colocating your compute and storage in the same region eliminates transfer charges. Cross-region S3 to EC2 transfer is charged. Outbound to the internet from S3 is charged at $0.09/GB for the first 10 TB."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company receives a large AWS bill driven by NAT Gateway processing fees. Their EC2 instances in private subnets are frequently accessing S3 and DynamoDB. What architecture change eliminates these NAT Gateway charges?","options":["A. Move all EC2 instances to public subnets","B. Create VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB — traffic routes directly from the VPC to these services without going through the NAT Gateway, eliminating NAT processing fees for this traffic","C. Use S3 Transfer Acceleration to bypass NAT Gateway","D. Switch from NAT Gateway to a NAT Instance to reduce costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB are free (no endpoint charges) and route traffic directly from the VPC to the service without going through the NAT Gateway. This eliminates both NAT Gateway data processing charges ($0.045/GB) for S3/DynamoDB traffic. Moving to public subnets exposes instances. Transfer Acceleration is for upload speed. NAT Instances reduce per-GB cost slightly but require management."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is running a production workload on ec2 m5.4xlarge instances (16 vCPU / 64 GB). They're considering migrating to AWS Graviton (m7g.4xlarge — 16 vCPU / 64 GB). What is the expected cost benefit?","options":["A. Graviton instances cost more but provide better performance","B. AWS Graviton instances provide comparable or better performance at approximately 20% lower cost — m7g is typically 20-40% cheaper than equivalent x86 instances with similar or better performance for many workloads","C. Graviton instances are only cheaper for Lambda, not EC2","D. Graviton (ARM) requires complete application re-architecture for all workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Graviton3 (m7g) instances provide 20-40% better price-performance than equivalent x86 instances. Most modern application workloads (Java, Python, Node.js, .NET, Go, Ruby) run on ARM without code changes. Application binaries may need recompilation but not re-architecture. Lambda Graviton is also cheaper. Cost savings typically justify migration testing for any significant EC2 spend."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Kinesis Data Streams and is paying for 24 shards that handle daily peak traffic. At night, traffic drops to 10% of peak. Shard costs are charged per shard-hour regardless of traffic. What reduces costs?","options":["A. Delete and recreate the stream daily based on traffic","B. Use Kinesis Data Streams on-demand mode — it automatically scales shards with traffic and charges per GB ingested instead of per shard-hour, saving cost during low-traffic periods","C. Reduce the number of shards to 3 to cut costs","D. Use SQS instead of Kinesis to avoid shard costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Kinesis on-demand mode eliminates shard management and charges per GB ingested rather than per shard-hour. For streams with 10:1 peak-to-off-peak ratios, on-demand can be significantly cheaper than 24 idle shards at night. Reducing to 3 shards saves cost but causes throttling at peak. SQS migration changes the streaming architecture fundamentally. Delete/recreate is operationally complex and risks downtime."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is building a new application and wants to choose the most cost-effective AWS database service for a relational workload with read-heavy access patterns. The workload has predictable traffic and requires 99.99% availability. Which database configuration minimizes cost?","options":["A. Amazon RDS Multi-AZ for high availability with Read Replicas for reads","B. Amazon Aurora MySQL with Aurora Replicas — Aurora provides better price-performance than RDS, and Aurora Replicas serve both reads and failover (HA), combining the functions of Read Replicas and Multi-AZ standby","C. Amazon DynamoDB — it's always cheaper than RDS for relational workloads","D. Amazon RDS on dedicated instances for better per-unit pricing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora MySQL provides up to 5x better performance than RDS MySQL at a similar price point. Aurora Replicas can serve reads AND provide automatic failover (replacing the need for a separate Multi-AZ standby), giving you HA + read scaling in one. RDS Multi-AZ + Read Replicas requires separate standby and replica instances. DynamoDB is NoSQL and not suitable for relational workloads. Dedicated instances are more expensive."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company's AWS bill shows significant charges for CloudWatch Logs storage. They have hundreds of log groups with no retention policy set (default: indefinite retention). What is the fastest cost reduction action?","options":["A. Disable CloudWatch Logs for all services","B. Set CloudWatch Logs retention policies on all log groups to delete logs after a defined period (e.g., 30-90 days) — logs beyond the retention period are automatically deleted, eliminating storage charges","C. Export all logs to S3 and then delete from CloudWatch","D. Compress log entries using a Lambda function"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch Logs without retention policies accumulate indefinitely at $0.03/GB/month storage. Setting retention to 30-90 days (depending on compliance requirements) automatically deletes old logs, significantly reducing storage costs. This is a quick, low-risk action. Exporting to S3 is reasonable for long-term compliance storage (S3 is cheaper) but takes time to implement. Disabling logs removes operational visibility. Compression reduces size but logs still accumulate indefinitely."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company wants to reduce costs for their Amazon EC2 workloads. AWS Cost Explorer shows 60% of their EC2 spend is on On-Demand instances that have been running continuously for 8+ months. What is the recommended action?","options":["A. Purchase 3-year No Upfront Reserved Instances","B. Purchase Compute Savings Plans — they provide up to 66% savings, apply automatically across any instance family, size, OS, or region unlike standard RIs, offering flexibility for changing instance types","C. Convert all instances to Spot Instances","D. Increase instance sizes to get volume discounts"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans apply automatically to any EC2 usage regardless of instance family, size, region, or OS. They provide up to 66% savings with a 1 or 3-year commitment. Standard RIs are locked to specific instance type and region. Savings Plans provide similar savings with more flexibility — if you change instance types, the savings plan still applies. Spot is only appropriate for fault-tolerant workloads. Volume discounts don't exist in EC2 pricing."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company needs to process large genomics files stored in S3. Each file is 100 GB. The processing is done by an AWS Lambda function. The Lambda function needs access to the file contents. What is the cost-optimized approach to avoid downloading the entire file for partial processing?","options":["A. Download the entire 100 GB file to Lambda /tmp (10 GB max — this won't work)","B. Use S3 Select to retrieve only the relevant subset of data from the large file using SQL expressions, reducing data transfer and Lambda execution time","C. Use S3 Batch Operations to process all files simultaneously","D. Mount EFS in Lambda and copy the S3 file to EFS for faster access"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Select retrieves only the data matching a SQL expression from within an object, reducing data scanned and transferred by up to 80%. This is ideal for processing specific fields or rows from large files. Lambda /tmp storage is limited to 10 GB (10,240 MB) — insufficient for a 100 GB file. S3 Batch Operations is for running Lambda across many S3 objects, not filtering within objects. EFS mounting adds complexity and cost."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Fargate for their containerized applications. After a cost review, they find they're paying for containers that run 24/7 but are only actively serving traffic during business hours (9 AM - 6 PM). What is the cost-optimized solution?","options":["A. Move all containers to EC2 Reserved Instances to reduce hourly costs","B. Use Application Auto Scaling scheduled scaling to scale ECS tasks to 0 outside business hours and scale up before business hours begin — Fargate charges only for running tasks","C. Purchase Fargate Compute Savings Plans","D. Use smaller Fargate task sizes to reduce hourly costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fargate charges for CPU and memory per-second for running tasks. Scaling to 0 tasks outside business hours eliminates all compute charges for those periods. Scheduled scaling (scale down at 6 PM, scale up at 8:45 AM) automates this. Savings Plans provide discounts for consistent usage — not helpful for tasks that should be shut down. Smaller tasks reduce hourly rate but still run 24/7."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores 1 million small files (average 10 KB) in Amazon S3 Standard. They plan to access each file rarely — about once per year. S3 Intelligent-Tiering was suggested. What is a concern with using Intelligent-Tiering for small files?","options":["A. Intelligent-Tiering doesn't work with small files","B. S3 Intelligent-Tiering has a per-object monitoring and automation fee ($0.0025 per 1,000 objects). For 1 million files at 10 KB, the monitoring fee per GB is higher than the storage savings — making Standard or Standard-IA cheaper","C. Intelligent-Tiering has high retrieval fees for small files","D. Intelligent-Tiering is only for files larger than 1 TB"],"answer":1,"explain":"Intelligent-Tiering charges $0.0025 per 1,000 objects/month for monitoring. For 1 million objects, that's $2.50/month monitoring fee regardless of object size. 1 million × 10 KB = 10 GB, costing ~$0.23/month in Standard. The monitoring fee ($2.50) exceeds the storage cost ($0.23). AWS recommends Intelligent-Tiering only for objects larger than 128 KB (larger objects have higher storage costs that justify the monitoring fee)."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs a web application with an ALB and Auto Scaling group. During off-peak hours, the minimum instance count is 2 but CloudWatch shows CPU at 2% on both instances. What cost optimization should be implemented?","options":["A. Delete the application load balancer to save costs","B. Reduce the minimum instance count to 1 if the application can tolerate brief capacity reduction during scale-out events, or migrate to a serverless architecture (Lambda) if traffic patterns suit it","C. Purchase Reserved Instances for the 2 minimum instances","D. Enable EC2 Hibernate to pause idle instances while keeping them reserved"],"answer":1,"explain":"If the application can tolerate the brief period (typically 2-5 minutes) for Auto Scaling to launch a second instance when needed, reducing minimum to 1 halves the minimum capacity cost. For dramatically variable workloads (near-zero off-peak), migrating to Lambda may be even more cost-effective. Purchasing RIs for 2 instances provides discounts but doesn't reduce running costs. Hibernate isn't supported for all instance types and the instance is still reserved."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company has Lambda functions invoked by SQS. Each Lambda invocation processes 1 message. Messages average 2 KB. The function runs for 100ms. They're looking to optimize cost. What change has the greatest impact?","options":["A. Reduce Lambda memory from 1024 MB to 128 MB","B. Configure SQS batch size of 10 in the Lambda event source mapping — 1 Lambda invocation processes 10 messages instead of 1, reducing invocation count (and cost) by 90% with no impact on processing logic","C. Switch from SQS to SNS to reduce queue costs","D. Use Lambda SnapStart to reduce execution duration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda charges per invocation and per GB-second. Increasing SQS batch size to 10 reduces Lambda invocations by 90% (same messages, 10x fewer invocations) while keeping the same total GB-seconds for processing. This is the highest-impact optimization. Reducing memory from 1024 MB may affect performance (test first). SNS doesn't queue messages. SnapStart is for Java, and the function duration is already minimal at 100ms."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is designing a data archival solution. Data must be retained for 10 years and retrieved within 48 hours when needed (compliance audit scenarios — infrequent). What is the most cost-effective storage solution?","options":["A. Amazon S3 Standard — reliable and always available","B. Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive — at $0.00099/GB/month it is the lowest-cost AWS storage option, with 12-hour Standard and 48-hour Bulk retrieval meeting the 48-hour requirement","C. Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval","D. Amazon EBS Cold HDD (sc1) volumes"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Glacier Deep Archive at ~$1/TB/month is the cheapest AWS storage, designed for data accessed less than once per year. With 48-hour retrieval SLAs for compliance audits, Standard retrieval (12 hours) or Bulk retrieval (48 hours) meet the requirement. S3 Standard costs ~$23/TB/month — 23x more expensive. Glacier Flexible Retrieval costs ~$4/TB/month. EBS volumes are for block storage, not archival."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company receives inconsistent traffic with very low baseline usage but occasional 100x traffic spikes. They're currently using EC2 with Auto Scaling but paying for minimum EC2 instances even at low traffic. What architecture reduces baseline costs to near-zero?","options":["A. Use EC2 Spot Instances for the entire fleet","B. Migrate to a serverless architecture (API Gateway + Lambda + DynamoDB on-demand) — costs scale linearly from near-zero with actual usage, and AWS manages scaling transparently","C. Reduce minimum Auto Scaling group size to 0","D. Use Amazon Lightsail for lower-cost instances at baseline"],"answer":1,"explain":"Serverless architectures have no idle cost. Lambda charges per invocation and duration only. API Gateway charges per API call. DynamoDB on-demand charges per request. Total cost at low traffic approaches zero. Auto Scaling minimum of 0 is possible but creates cold-start issues for EC2 (5-10 minutes). Spot Instances save cost but still charge per running hour. Lightsail has fixed monthly pricing, not variable."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company's AWS Config costs have grown unexpectedly. They enable Config in 20 AWS regions across 10 accounts. Analysis shows Config is recording all resource types including many they don't need. What reduces Config costs?","options":["A. Disable Config in all non-production accounts","B. Configure Config to record only specific resource types that are relevant to compliance requirements — excluding unnecessary resource types reduces the number of configuration items recorded and associated costs","C. Enable Config Snapshot delivery only (disable stream delivery)","D. Use AWS Security Hub instead of Config for all compliance monitoring"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config charges per configuration item recorded. Selecting only the resource types required for compliance (e.g., EC2, S3, IAM, RDS) instead of recording all resource types significantly reduces the volume of configuration items and costs. Disabling Config in non-production accounts reduces coverage but may violate compliance requirements. Config rules and recording are separate — recording all types with no rules still generates costs. Security Hub uses Config as a data source."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon RDS and is looking for ways to reduce database costs. Their MySQL workload runs 24/7 but has clear predictable steady-state usage. What is the most cost-effective change?","options":["A. Move to RDS Multi-AZ to get better pricing per unit","B. Purchase Reserved DB Instances for the RDS workload — 1-year partial upfront provides ~40% savings; 3-year all upfront provides ~60% savings over On-Demand pricing","C. Enable RDS storage autoscaling to right-size storage","D. Use Amazon Aurora Serverless for the MySQL workload — always cheaper"],"answer":1,"explain":"RDS Reserved Instances provide up to 60% discount for 1-year (partial upfront) or 3-year (all upfront) commitments for predictable 24/7 workloads. Multi-AZ doubles the cost per instance. Storage autoscaling manages storage, not compute pricing. Aurora Serverless charges per ACU-hour and at high steady-state usage can cost more than a provisioned Aurora or RDS Reserved Instance."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company has a large amount of infrequently accessed data in Amazon DynamoDB. Read costs are acceptable but storage costs are high due to data that hasn't been accessed in 2+ years. What is the most cost-effective approach?","options":["A. Increase DynamoDB provisioned capacity to speed up data retrieval and deletion","B. Use DynamoDB Time to Live (TTL) to automatically delete expired items at no charge, and export aged data to S3 using DynamoDB export for cold archival storage at 75% less cost than DynamoDB","C. Migrate the entire DynamoDB table to Amazon RDS for cheaper storage","D. Enable DynamoDB auto-scaling to reduce storage costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB TTL automatically deletes items past their expiration at no additional cost. For data needing archival (not deletion), DynamoDB export to S3 provides the data at S3 storage prices (~$0.023/GB vs ~$0.25/GB for DynamoDB). This combination manages the full data lifecycle. Auto-scaling manages throughput capacity, not storage costs. RDS migration changes the data model."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company deployed an application to AWS using CloudFormation. The template creates the same environment across dev, test, staging, and production. Development environments are used 9 AM - 6 PM on weekdays only. What is the simplest cost-optimization approach for dev/test?","options":["A. Create cheaper CloudFormation templates for dev/test with smaller instance types","B. Use AWS Instance Scheduler integrated with CloudFormation tags — automatically stop and start dev/test resources based on schedule, reducing running hours by 75% for weekday-only usage","C. Delete and recreate dev environments daily using CloudFormation","D. Use Spot Instances in dev/test CloudFormation stacks"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Instance Scheduler uses resource tags to automatically stop and start EC2 and RDS instances based on defined schedules. Tagging dev/test resources with an 'office-hours' schedule reduces active hours from 168/week to ~45/week — a 73% reduction in compute costs. Delete/recreate via CloudFormation takes time and risks configuration drift. Spot Instances help with compute cost but still run 24/7. Smaller instances help but hourly charges still accumulate overnight."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company reviews their AWS bill and notices they're paying $50,000/month for data transfer out to the internet. Most of this is serving static assets (images, CSS, JS) directly from S3 to users. What architectural change could dramatically reduce these costs?","options":["A. Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration — it reduces data transfer costs","B. Place Amazon CloudFront in front of S3 — CloudFront data transfer rates are up to 50% cheaper than direct S3 transfer rates, and CloudFront caching reduces the volume of S3 GET requests","C. Switch to S3 Reduced Redundancy Storage for static assets","D. Use AWS Direct Connect for all end-user data transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront data transfer to internet is up to 50% cheaper than S3 data transfer to internet. Additionally, CloudFront caching reduces origin fetches to S3, lowering both S3 GET request counts and S3 data transfer costs. For $50K/month, CloudFront could reduce costs by $25K+/month. S3 Transfer Acceleration increases transfer speed to S3, not from S3 to users. Direct Connect is for enterprise on-premises connections."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs many EC2 instances of different types across multiple regions. They want a single purchasing commitment that maximizes savings across their diverse, changing fleet without being locked to specific instance types. Which option provides this?","options":["A. EC2 Instance Savings Plans — apply to specific instance families per region","B. Compute Savings Plans — apply to any EC2 instance regardless of family, size, region, tenancy, or OS; also apply to Fargate and Lambda","C. Regional Reserved Instances — flexible within a region","D. Standard Reserved Instances — highest discount but least flexible"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans are the most flexible commitment-based discount. They apply automatically to any EC2 instance usage (any family, size, region, OS), Fargate tasks, and Lambda invocations. When the fleet changes (e.g., switching from m5 to m6g, or from one region to another), the Savings Plan continues to apply. Instance Savings Plans only apply to a specific instance family per region. Standard RIs are locked to specific instance type and region."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company's cost analysis shows S3 request costs are unexpectedly high. Investigation reveals a Lambda function that processes S3 events is performing a HeadObject API call on every event to get object metadata, even though metadata is available in the S3 event notification itself. What is the fix?","options":["A. Switch from S3 event notifications to S3 Batch Operations","B. Modify the Lambda function to extract object metadata (size, content-type, ETag) directly from the S3 event notification payload instead of making an additional HeadObject API call — eliminates 100% of those S3 request charges","C. Enable S3 Requester Pays to shift API costs to requesters","D. Cache HeadObject results in ElastiCache to reduce repeated calls"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 event notifications include object metadata (size, ETag, content-type) in the event payload. Making an additional HeadObject call is redundant and incurs S3 LIST/GET request charges ($0.0004 per 1,000 requests). Eliminating these calls from the Lambda function reduces both S3 API costs and Lambda execution time. Caching helps but HeadObject is still called once per unique object. Batch Operations changes the processing model."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores 10 TB of application logs in Amazon S3 in JSON format. They run Athena queries daily to analyze the data but pay high Athena scan costs. The JSON files are not partitioned and are each 1-5 MB. What is the most effective cost reduction for Athena?","options":["A. Run Athena queries during off-peak hours for lower cost","B. Convert JSON to Apache Parquet format using AWS Glue ETL and partition data by date in S3 — Parquet columnar format reduces data scanned by 60-90%, and date partitions allow queries to scan only relevant time periods","C. Increase Athena query timeout to scan more data per query","D. Use Athena workgroups to limit per-query scan costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Athena charges $5 per TB scanned. Parquet's columnar format means Athena reads only the columns in your SELECT clause (not entire rows), reducing scanned data by 60-90%. Date-based partitioning ensures queries with date filters scan only relevant partitions. This combination typically reduces Athena costs by 70-90%. Athena pricing doesn't change by time of day. Workgroup scan limits prevent runaway queries but don't reduce the cost of necessary queries."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company needs to run a high-performance computing (HPC) simulation that takes 2 hours on 100 c5n.18xlarge instances. The simulation runs twice per week. What is the cost-optimized compute strategy?","options":["A. Keep 100 c5n.18xlarge instances running 24/7 for immediate availability","B. Purchase Reserved Instances for 100 c5n.18xlarge instances","C. Use EC2 Spot Instances with a Spot Fleet configured for the HPC workload — leverage checkpointing and placement groups; Spot provides up to 90% savings for this interruptible batch workload","D. Use AWS Fargate for the HPC simulation"],"answer":2,"explain":"HPC simulations are ideal Spot candidates: fault-tolerant (can checkpoint), short-duration (2 hours), and run on a schedule (not time-critical to the minute). Spot Instances provide up to 90% savings. With 100 × c5n.18xlarge × 2 hours × 2/week, On-Demand would cost ~$6,000/week; Spot ~$600/week. Running 24/7 is ~$84,000/week in On-Demand costs — 140x more expensive. RIs for 100 large instances is expensive for 4 hours/week of actual use. Fargate doesn't support HPC networking requirements."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Lambda and notices high costs from a function invoked every minute by EventBridge to poll a database for new records. The function rarely finds new records. What architecture reduces invocation costs?","options":["A. Reduce polling frequency to every 5 minutes","B. Replace polling with an event-driven architecture — trigger Lambda via DynamoDB Streams, RDS events, or an application-layer event when records are actually inserted, eliminating unnecessary invocations when no records exist","C. Increase Lambda memory to process polling faster","D. Cache database query results in ElastiCache to speed up empty polls"],"answer":1,"explain":"Polling (pulling) for new records wastes Lambda invocations when nothing has changed. Event-driven architecture (pushing) triggers Lambda only when records are actually inserted (via DynamoDB Streams, SQS, SNS, or EventBridge events from the database). This can reduce invocations by 99%+ if records arrive infrequently. Reducing frequency to 5 minutes still wastes invocations. Caching empty results doesn't reduce Lambda invocations."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon EBS and has 500 volumes provisioned with 1,000 IOPS each (io1 type). Analysis shows 80% of volumes never exceed 100 IOPS. What is the cost-optimized action?","options":["A. Delete all underutilized volumes","B. Downgrade the 80% underutilized volumes from io1 (1,000 IOPS) to gp3 — gp3 provides 3,000 IOPS baseline at a lower cost per GB and can be provisioned at exactly the needed IOPS level, saving 50-70% on those volumes","C. Convert all io1 volumes to instance store","D. Enable EBS burst mode on io1 volumes to reduce provisioned IOPS"],"answer":1,"explain":"io1 charges per provisioned IOPS ($0.065/provisioned IOPS-month). Switching to gp3 includes 3,000 IOPS for the base price (~$0.08/GB-month) with no per-IOPS charge up to 3,000 IOPS. Volumes actually using only 100 IOPS pay for 1,000 provisioned IOPS unnecessarily on io1. gp3 saves ~50-70% for most of these volumes. Deleting volumes removes data. Instance store cannot be replaced with EBS volumes dynamically. io1 doesn't have burst mode like gp2."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company wants to identify which AWS services are driving unexpected cost increases month-over-month. What is the first step in their cost investigation?","options":["A. Contact AWS Support for a bill review","B. Use AWS Cost Explorer with service-level grouping and month-over-month cost comparison filters to identify which services, regions, and accounts have the highest cost growth","C. Review all CloudTrail API calls to identify new resource creation","D. Enable AWS Budgets with an alert for any monthly cost exceeding last month's spend"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer provides visualization of costs by service, region, account, and tag with time comparisons. Grouping by service and comparing current month to previous months immediately identifies which services have unexpected increases. CloudTrail shows API calls but not aggregated costs. AWS Budgets alerts on threshold breaches but doesn't identify root causes. AWS Support can help but should come after internal investigation."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs a media encoding service with inconsistent job submission patterns. Some days have 10 jobs, others have 500. They use EC2 instances with a custom encoding application. What is the most cost-effective architecture for this workload?","options":["A. Provision EC2 instances for peak load (500 jobs) and run them 24/7","B. Use AWS Elemental MediaConvert (managed service) for media encoding — pay per minute of video processed with no idle infrastructure costs; scale from 0 to 500 jobs without provisioning","C. Use EC2 Spot Instances with Auto Scaling — scale from 0 to 500 instances based on queue depth","D. Purchase Reserved Instances for the average number of daily jobs"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Elemental MediaConvert is a managed media encoding service that scales automatically and charges per minute of encoded video — zero idle cost. This perfectly matches the highly variable workload (10-500 jobs). EC2 Spot with Auto Scaling is a valid self-managed alternative but requires maintaining infrastructure. Reserved Instances for average load means either under-capacity on heavy days or idle capacity on light days."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A startup is building a new application on AWS and wants to minimize costs during development while maintaining a realistic test environment. What approach is recommended?","options":["A. Develop everything on a single large EC2 instance to simplify costs","B. Use AWS Free Tier services where available, deploy smaller instance types in dev (scale up for production), use Aurora Serverless v2 with minimum ACU for dev databases, and leverage Spot Instances for development EC2","C. Use the same production-size infrastructure for development to ensure accurate performance testing","D. Develop locally on laptops and only deploy to AWS for final testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"A cost-conscious development approach combines Free Tier usage (Lambda 1M free invocations/month, DynamoDB 25 GB free, EC2 750 hours t2.micro), smaller dev instance sizes, Aurora Serverless (scales to near zero when idle), and Spot Instances for dev EC2. This can reduce dev/test costs by 80-90%. Production-size dev environments are expensive and unnecessary for functional testing. Local development is valuable but cloud services need cloud testing."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Organizations with 50 accounts. They want to apply a single discount strategy across all accounts for EC2. Which purchasing option applies organization-wide automatically?","options":["A. Purchase Reserved Instances in each member account separately","B. Compute Savings Plans in the management account — the discount applies across all accounts in the organization through billing consolidation","C. Enable RI sharing in each member account","D. Use Spot Instances across all accounts for cost savings"],"answer":1,"explain":"Savings Plans and Reserved Instances purchased in the management (payer) account apply across all member accounts through consolidated billing. Compute Savings Plans automatically apply to the highest-cost usage across the organization. No action is needed in individual accounts beyond keeping RI sharing enabled (default). Individual account purchases are less efficient for organization-wide cost optimization."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores user profile images in Amazon S3 and serves them via an application server. The application currently downloads each image from S3 and re-serves it to the end user, doubling data transfer costs. What change eliminates double transfer?","options":["A. Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration on the bucket","B. Generate S3 pre-signed URLs and return them directly to the client — the client downloads the image directly from S3, eliminating the application server data transfer hop and associated costs","C. Cache images on the application server EBS volume","D. Use S3 Select to serve partial image data"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-signed URLs allow clients to download directly from S3, bypassing the application server. This eliminates: (1) S3-to-EC2 transfer (though intra-region is free), and (2) EC2-to-internet data transfer charges (the most expensive leg). The client pays for one S3-to-internet transfer instead of S3-to-EC2-to-internet. CloudFront is another option for cached, frequently accessed images."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is building a data lake on Amazon S3. They use multiple AWS accounts for different business units. Cross-account S3 data transfer is generating unexpected costs. What architectural change reduces cross-account transfer costs?","options":["A. Use VPC peering between accounts for S3 access","B. Use S3 access points with account-level permissions — different accounts access the same S3 bucket in the data lake owner's account, eliminating cross-account data copies","C. Move data to each account's local S3 bucket","D. Use AWS DataSync for cross-account data access"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 access points allow multiple AWS accounts to access a centralized S3 bucket with appropriate permissions. Data stays in one location — no copies are needed across accounts. Cross-account S3 access within the same region has no data transfer cost (intra-region S3 access is free even cross-account). Copying data to each account duplicates storage costs. DataSync is for replication/migration, not concurrent cross-account access."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company has 200 Lambda functions in production. A monthly cost review shows 150 functions are allocated 3 GB of memory but average memory usage is only 200 MB. What is the cost impact and recommended action?","options":["A. Lambda memory allocation doesn't affect cost — only execution time matters","B. Lambda charges per GB-second; allocating 3 GB for functions using only 200 MB wastes 93% of allocated memory cost — right-size these functions to 256 MB, reducing Lambda cost by approximately 91% for those functions","C. Reduce Lambda concurrent executions to save costs","D. Consolidate 150 functions into 10 larger functions to reduce overhead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda bills per GB-second. A function allocated 3 GB costs 15x more than the same function at 200 MB (the optimal allocation). Right-sizing 150 functions from 3 GB to 256 MB reduces their cost by ~91%. AWS Lambda Power Tuning is an open-source tool that finds the cost-optimal memory setting. Reducing concurrency limits availability. Consolidation changes architecture."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Route 53 for DNS. They have 100 health checks configured, each checking every 10 seconds. After a cost review, they find Route 53 health check costs are significant. How can they reduce costs while maintaining coverage?","options":["A. Disable all health checks — they're optional","B. Increase health check interval to 30 seconds for non-critical endpoints (reducing cost by 67% per check) and consolidate health checks where possible — use calculated health checks to combine multiple endpoint checks","C. Switch from HTTP health checks to TCP health checks","D. Move DNS to an external provider to avoid Route 53 health check costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 charges per health check per month, and fast health checks (10s interval) cost 3x more than standard (30s interval). Increasing to 30s for non-critical endpoints and using calculated health checks (which combine multiple health checks and cost less than individual checks) reduces costs significantly. TCP vs HTTP check pricing is the same. Moving to an external DNS provider may increase costs elsewhere and lose AWS integration."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs Amazon EMR clusters for daily batch processing. Each cluster runs for 6 hours then terminates. They use On-Demand pricing for the master and core nodes, and Spot for task nodes. The master node is a large instance type. What additional cost optimization is possible?","options":["A. Use Spot Instances for master and core nodes as well","B. Right-size the master node — the EMR master node is a coordinator that doesn't process data directly; it often only needs a small/medium instance, potentially saving 50-80% on the master node cost","C. Use Reserved Instances for the EMR master node","D. Eliminate the task nodes and use only core nodes"],"answer":1,"explain":"The EMR master node manages the cluster (YARN ResourceManager, HDFS NameNode) but doesn't process data. For most workloads, a m5.xlarge or m5.2xlarge master node is sufficient vs. using the same large instance as worker nodes. RIs for transient 6-hour clusters don't provide value (RI is hourly; a 6-hour cluster benefits but the utilization is low compared to commitment). Spot for master/core risks cluster instability."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores log data in Amazon OpenSearch Service (Elasticsearch). After 30 days, logs are rarely queried but must be retained for 1 year for compliance. The OpenSearch cluster is sized to store 365 days of logs, which is expensive. What is the cost-optimized solution?","options":["A. Delete logs older than 30 days from OpenSearch","B. Use OpenSearch UltraWarm or Cold storage tiers for logs older than 30 days — UltraWarm costs significantly less than hot storage and data can be moved back to hot tier for queries when needed","C. Move logs to RDS after 30 days for cheaper storage","D. Compress log documents in OpenSearch to reduce storage"],"answer":1,"explain":"OpenSearch UltraWarm storage costs ~87% less than hot storage. Cold storage costs even less. Data can be moved from hot → UltraWarm → Cold automatically via Index State Management (ISM) policies. Logs older than 30 days are rarely queried but available when needed after moving to UltraWarm. This allows the active cluster to be sized for 30 days while retaining 1 year of data cost-effectively."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses AWS WAF to protect their application. They have 30 web ACLs deployed across multiple CloudFront distributions and ALBs. AWS WAF costs are significant. What is a cost optimization strategy?","options":["A. Disable WAF on development environments","B. Consolidate WAF rules into a smaller number of rule groups shared across web ACLs using AWS Firewall Manager, reducing the number of active web ACLs and rule groups while maintaining protection","C. Switch from WAF to Security Groups for DDoS protection","D. Remove all managed rule groups and write all custom rules"],"answer":1,"explain":"WAF charges per web ACL per month and per rule/rule group. AWS Firewall Manager allows centrally managing WAF policies across accounts and resources, ensuring consistent protection with fewer redundant rule groups. Disabling WAF on dev reduces cost but removes protection. Security Groups don't provide L7 protection. Custom rules require significant development effort and expertise."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon Redshift. Their cluster utilization shows 95% memory usage and slow query performance. They're considering upgrading to larger nodes. What should they evaluate first to ensure cost-effectiveness?","options":["A. Immediately upgrade to larger nodes — performance issues justify any cost","B. First analyze Redshift Advisor recommendations, consider VACUUM and ANALYZE to reclaim space and update statistics, evaluate data distribution and sort keys, and consider Redshift Spectrum to offload cold data to S3 before purchasing larger nodes","C. Add more nodes to the cluster without changing node size","D. Enable Redshift automatic table optimization and wait for it to resolve performance issues"],"answer":1,"explain":"Before adding expensive capacity, optimization should be explored: VACUUM reclaims storage from deleted rows (improving memory usage), ANALYZE updates query planner statistics, distribution key improvements reduce data movement, and moving cold data to S3 via Spectrum can dramatically reduce cluster storage requirements. These are free optimizations. Adding nodes or upgrading is expensive and may not be necessary after optimization."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company processes 1 billion small transactions per day in DynamoDB. They're on provisioned capacity and auto-scaling. Cost Explorer shows DynamoDB is their largest cost. What should they investigate for potential savings?","options":["A. Migrate to RDS for cheaper transaction processing","B. Evaluate DynamoDB Standard-IA table class for tables with infrequent reads — if read/write ratio is low, Standard-IA reduces storage costs by 60% with the same performance","C. Reduce DynamoDB item size to reduce storage costs","D. Switch to DynamoDB on-demand mode for all tables"],"answer":1,"explain":"DynamoDB Standard-IA (Infrequent Access) table class reduces storage costs by 60% but increases read/write request costs. It's cost-effective for tables with high storage but lower throughput requirements. For tables that store lots of data but aren't heavily read/written (common for audit logs, historical data), Standard-IA is cheaper overall. On-demand mode adds flexibility but may cost more than well-tuned provisioned capacity at 1B daily transactions."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company has multiple Amazon ECS services running in separate VPCs across different accounts. Services communicate via internet-facing ALBs, generating data transfer costs and security concerns. What architecture reduces both cost and security risk?","options":["A. Enable VPC peering between all VPCs to eliminate internet routing","B. Use AWS PrivateLink to expose services — consuming VPCs connect to interface VPC endpoints, traffic stays on AWS private network, eliminating internet data transfer charges and reducing attack surface","C. Merge all services into a single VPC to eliminate cross-VPC traffic","D. Use Direct Connect for all inter-service communication"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS PrivateLink provides private connectivity between VPCs (even cross-account) without internet exposure. Data transfer via PrivateLink is cheaper than internet-routed traffic. It's also more secure — no public IPs or internet exposure needed. VPC peering creates a full mesh which becomes complex with many VPCs. Merging VPCs requires significant re-architecture. Direct Connect is for on-premises to AWS connectivity."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company's AWS monthly bill is $200,000. After initial analysis, they find 40% of costs are from EC2 instances running 24/7 with no reservation. They also see 20% of costs are S3 Standard storage for data untouched for 6 months. What is the priority order for cost optimization actions?","options":["A. Fix S3 storage class first as it's simpler, then address EC2","B. Address EC2 first (highest spend, highest potential savings with RIs/Savings Plans at 40-60% savings on $80K = $32-48K/month), then implement S3 lifecycle policies for infrequently accessed data ($40K × 80% lifecycle savings = $32K/month)","C. Both actions should be taken simultaneously — hire a team to handle both","D. Contact AWS Enterprise Support for a discount negotiation first"],"answer":1,"explain":"Prioritize by impact: EC2 at 40% of spend ($80K) with 40-60% savings potential = $32-48K/month savings. S3 lifecycle at 20% ($40K) with 80% storage class savings = $32K/month. Both are important but EC2 has slightly higher first-year savings and faster implementation with Savings Plans (no per-instance management). The correct answer focuses on the systematic approach: highest spend first. Both should be done — B correctly prioritizes by impact."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is evaluating whether to use Kinesis Data Firehose or custom Lambda + S3 code for log delivery. The logs need to be delivered to S3. Which is more cost-effective at scale?","options":["A. Custom Lambda + S3 is always cheaper because you control the code","B. Kinesis Data Firehose is typically more cost-effective — charges per GB ingested with no infrastructure to manage, while custom Lambda + S3 requires paying for Lambda execution, SQS or Kinesis for buffering, and engineering time","C. Both solutions cost exactly the same at scale","D. Kinesis Data Firehose is only cost-effective below 1 GB/day"],"answer":1,"explain":"Firehose charges $0.029/GB ingested with automatic batching, compression, and S3 delivery. Custom Lambda solutions require Lambda execution cost, SQS or Kinesis trigger cost, engineering time, and maintenance. For most log delivery use cases, Firehose is simpler and cheaper. Only at very high scale (hundreds of TB/day) might custom solutions be cheaper. Operational simplicity of Firehose also has significant value."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company needs to run a containerized application that processes work items from an SQS queue. The queue typically has 0 items but occasionally receives thousands. What is the most cost-effective architecture?","options":["A. Run a fixed number of ECS Fargate tasks to poll the queue","B. Use KEDA (Kubernetes Event-driven Autoscaling) on EKS to scale from 0 to thousands of pods based on SQS queue depth, or use Lambda with SQS event source mapping — scale from 0 with no idle costs","C. Use EC2 Auto Scaling with SQS metric scaling","D. Use ECS with Application Auto Scaling — it scales on SQS queue depth"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda with SQS event source mapping is the most cost-effective: Lambda scales from 0 invocations and charges per invocation only when there are messages. Zero cost at idle. ECS/Fargate task minimum is 1 task unless scaled to 0 (which introduces startup latency). KEDA on EKS also scales to 0 but requires cluster management. EC2 Auto Scaling has minimum instance costs. For sporadic, queue-driven workloads, Lambda is the natural cost-efficient choice."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses Amazon CloudFront and S3 for a global media website. They find that cache hit ratio is 40% — lower than expected. What investigation and improvement should they prioritize?","options":["A. Increase number of CloudFront edge locations","B. Analyze CloudFront cache statistics to identify low-cache-hit behaviors; common fixes include increasing object TTL, ensuring Cache-Control headers are set appropriately, removing unnecessary query strings from cache keys, and identifying objects that should be cached but aren't","C. Switch from S3 to EC2 origin for dynamic content","D. Enable CloudFront Lambda@Edge for all requests"],"answer":1,"explain":"A 40% cache hit ratio means 60% of requests go to the origin, paying for both CloudFront and S3 transfer costs. Investigation typically reveals: objects with TTL=0 that should be cached, query strings creating unique cache keys unnecessarily, or Cookie forwarding creating many cache variations. Raising TTL for static assets to hours/days is the most impactful fix. CloudFront cache statistics reports identify which paths have low hit ratios."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company runs scheduled AWS Glue ETL jobs. The jobs take 2-3 minutes to complete but they're being charged for 10 minutes minimum. How can they reduce Glue costs?","options":["A. Increase DPU allocation to finish jobs faster within the 10-minute minimum","B. For short-duration jobs under 10 minutes, consider using AWS Glue Flex execution (accepts excess capacity at discounted rates) or migrate short ETL logic to Lambda which charges per 1ms increment with no minimum","C. Schedule all Glue jobs to run simultaneously to maximize 10-minute billing windows","D. Use larger DPU counts to finish in under 1 minute"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Glue Standard jobs have a 1-minute minimum billing. Glue charges per second for jobs over 1 minute. However, for very short ETL tasks, Lambda (charges per 1ms with no minimum) or Python scripts on EC2 may be more cost-effective. Glue Flex mode accepts excess capacity at up to 34% discount but with non-guaranteed start time. The key insight is evaluating whether Glue is the right tool for sub-2-minute jobs."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company is designing a new multi-tier web application. The database tier is expected to have high read volume with occasional write spikes. They want to minimize database costs. What architecture provides the best cost optimization?","options":["A. Use Amazon RDS MySQL Multi-AZ for high availability and read replicas for reads","B. Use Amazon Aurora with Aurora Replicas — Aurora's distributed storage architecture means replicas don't duplicate storage costs (all replicas share the same underlying storage), providing read scaling at lower cost than RDS replicas which each have full storage copies","C. Use DynamoDB for the relational database workload","D. Use ElastiCache as the primary data store to minimize database costs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora Replicas share the same distributed storage volume as the primary — you don't pay for N copies of the storage for N replicas. RDS Read Replicas each have a full copy of the data, so storage costs multiply with each replica. For read-heavy workloads needing multiple read replicas, Aurora is more cost-effective in storage. Aurora also provides Aurora reader endpoint load balancing natively. DynamoDB doesn't serve relational workloads."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company wants to track their AWS costs by project and team across a single AWS account with hundreds of resources. What is the AWS-recommended approach for cost allocation?","options":["A. Create separate AWS accounts for each team and use consolidated billing","B. Apply AWS resource tags consistently (e.g., Project: ProjectA, Team: Engineering) and enable cost allocation tags in the Billing console — Cost Explorer can then break down costs by tag values","C. Use AWS Service Catalog to organize resources by team","D. Use CloudFormation StackSets to organize resources and track costs per stack"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cost allocation tags enabled in the Billing console allow Cost Explorer to filter and group costs by tag values. Consistent tagging (Project, Team, Environment, Owner) provides granular cost visibility without separate accounts. AWS provides tag enforcement tools (Config rules, SCP enforcement). Separate accounts provide stronger isolation but are heavier to manage. Service Catalog organizes deployments but doesn't provide cost allocation. CloudFormation stacks provide some grouping but not flexible tag-based cost allocation."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company uses AWS Direct Connect at 1 Gbps between their data center and AWS. They're also paying for a Site-to-Site VPN as backup. Direct Connect utilization averages 15%. How can they optimize costs?","options":["A. Cancel Direct Connect and use only the VPN backup","B. Evaluate whether a smaller Direct Connect port (100 Mbps or 500 Mbps via hosted connections) meets the bandwidth requirement at lower port cost, or use MACsec-encrypted 1 Gbps Direct Connect to eliminate the VPN cost if security was the VPN's purpose","C. Add more Direct Connect connections for redundancy","D. Switch to AWS Transit Gateway instead of Direct Connect"],"answer":1,"explain":"Direct Connect is charged per port-hour. A 1 Gbps port costs more than a 100 Mbps or 500 Mbps hosted connection (available via partners). At 15% utilization (~150 Mbps average), a 500 Mbps connection may suffice at lower cost. If the VPN was providing encryption for Direct Connect, MACsec on Direct Connect eliminates the need for a separate VPN. Canceling Direct Connect loses its performance and reliability benefits. Adding connections increases costs."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company stores 50 TB of data in Amazon EFS for a machine learning training workflow. Training jobs run once per week. Between runs, the data sits idle. What S3 cost optimization applies here?","options":["A. Delete data after each training run and reload next time","B. Use EFS Intelligent Tiering — data that hasn't been accessed for 7 days moves to EFS Infrequent Access (EFS-IA) storage at 92% lower cost automatically, while remaining instantly accessible for the next training run","C. Mount multiple EFS file systems to spread data across cheaper tiers","D. Replace EFS with S3 for machine learning training data"],"answer":1,"explain":"EFS Intelligent Tiering automatically moves files unused for 7 days to EFS-IA ($0.016/GB vs $0.30/GB for standard EFS in us-east-1 — ~92% savings). Files move back to standard storage instantly when accessed for the next training run. This is zero-code, zero-configuration after enabling Intelligent Tiering. Deleting and reloading data wastes time and compute. S3 with FSx for Lustre is another pattern but involves migration."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company wants to set up guardrails preventing AWS spending from exceeding $50,000 per month. They want automated action, not just alerts. What combination of services achieves this?","options":["A. AWS Budgets alert only — no automated actions available","B. AWS Budgets with budget actions — configure an action to apply a restrictive SCP or IAM policy to accounts when the budget threshold is reached, limiting further resource creation","C. AWS Cost Anomaly Detection with SNS notifications","D. AWS Trusted Advisor with automated cost optimization recommendations"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Budgets Actions can automatically apply SCPs, target EC2/RDS instances for stop/terminate, or apply IAM policies when budget thresholds are hit. This provides automated enforcement (not just alerting). Actions can be configured at 80%, 90%, and 100% of budget with escalating responses (alert → restrict → stop). Cost Anomaly Detection sends alerts only. Trusted Advisor provides recommendations but no enforcement."},{"cat":"cost-optimized-arch","q":"A company processes video files uploaded to S3. Processing happens immediately after upload using a Lambda trigger. They discover 40% of uploaded files are duplicates (same content, different filenames) and are being processed multiple times. What cost optimization reduces duplicate processing?","options":["A. Use S3 Object Lock to prevent duplicate uploads","B. Calculate a hash (MD5/SHA256) of each file on upload and check against a DynamoDB table of processed file hashes — skip processing if hash already exists, reducing duplicate Lambda processing costs by 40%","C. Use S3 Versioning to detect duplicate content","D. Use Amazon Rekognition to detect duplicate videos"],"answer":1,"explain":"Content-based deduplication using a hash stored in DynamoDB prevents reprocessing identical files. The Lambda function checks the DynamoDB hash table before processing — if the hash exists, skip. This reduces Lambda execution costs and downstream storage costs by 40% in this scenario. S3 Versioning tracks file versions, not content duplication. Rekognition is for video analysis, not deduplication. S3 Object Lock prevents deletion, not duplicate uploads."}];